Abana.desc: A river near the city of Damascus in modern-day Syria; Naaman, a Syrian military commander, believed the Abanah River to be superior to the Jordan River for healing from leprosy (2 Kings 5:9–14).

Abarim.desc: A mountain range in Moab, northeast of the Dead Sea, where Moses was shown the promised land (Numbers 27:12; Deuteronomy 32:49).

Abdon.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Asher that was assigned to the Gershonites.

Abel-beth-maacah.desc: A town in the territory of Naphtali in northern Israel. Joab, commander of David's army, besieged this town (2 Samuel 20:14–22).

Abel-keramim.desc: A village in the region of Ammon, east of the Jordan River, where Jephthah subdued the Ammonites (Judges 11:33).

Abel-meholah.desc: A town in Gilead, west of the Jordan River, where the prophet Elisha was born (1 Kings 19:16).

Abel-mizraim.desc: A location east of the Jordan River where Jacob's children mourned their father (Genesis  50:10-11).

Abel-shittim.desc: A location on the plains of Moab, across from Jericho, where the Israelites camped before crossing the Jordan River (Numbers 33:49); possibly another name for Shittim.

Abila.desc: Abila of Perea: A city in Perea, north of the Dead Sea; possibly Abel-Shittim.

AbilaLysaniou.desc: A city on the Abana River, northeast of Israel; capital of ancient Abilene.

Abilene.desc: A region around the city of Abila, northwest of Damascus, ruled over by Lysanias.

Abronah.desc: A location in the Sinai Peninsula, between Yotbathah and Ezion-Geber, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan (Numbers 33:34).

Accad.desc: A town in Mesopotamia, which was part of the kingdom of Nimrod in the region of Shinar.

Acco.desc: A seaport town on the coast of the Mediterranean in the territory of Asher; later known as Ptolemais.

Achaia.desc: A Roman province in Greece which included the northern part of the Peloponnese Peninsula and the city of Corinth. Many early Christian communities and missionary activities were located here.

AchorValley.desc: A valley on the northern border of the territory of Judah where Achan, who "caused trouble for Israel," was stoned and buried (Joshua 7:24–26); associated with trouble and punishment.

Achshaph.desc: A town in Canaan which was later part of an alliance under Jabin, king of Hazor, against the Israelites (Joshua 11:1). It was later part of the territory of Asher (Joshua 19:25).

Achzib.desc: Achzib of Judah: A town in the western foothills of the territory of Judah; possibly another name for Chezib.

Achzib.2.desc: Achzib of Asher: A coastal town in the territory of Asher, southwest of the city of Tyre.

Adadah.desc: A town in the Negev in the territory of Judah.

Adam.desc: A town east of the Jordan River, near Zarethan, close to where the Israelites crossed the river (Joshua 3:16).

Adamah.desc: A fortified town in the territory of Naphtali.

Adami-nekeb.desc: A border town in the territory of Naphtali.

Adasa.desc: A city near Beth-Horon where Judas Maccabeus defeated Nicanor, leader of the Syrian army (1 Maccabees 7:40)

Addan.desc: A town in Babylon from which a group of Jews returned to Judea (Ezra 2:59).

Addar.desc: A town on the southern border of the territory of Judah.

Adithaim.desc: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Admah.desc: A town near the Dead Sea destroyed with Sodom and Gomorrah (Deuteronomy 29:23).

Adoraim.desc: A town in the territory of Judah that was fortified by Jeroboam (2 Chronicles 11:9).

AdriaticSea.desc: A body of water between Italy and the Balkan Peninsula.

Adulis.desc: A seaport city in East Africa on the coast of the Red Sea.

Adullam.desc: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah where David and his men hid in a nearby cave (1 Samuel 22:1).

Adummim.desc: A mountain pass between Jerusalem and Jericho.

AegeanSea.desc: An arm of the Mediterranean Sea between Greece and Turkey.

Aenon.desc: A town near Salim and the Jordan River where John the Baptist was baptizing (John 3:23).

Ahava.desc: A canal or river in Babylonia where Ezra assembled a group of exiles who were returning to Jerusalem (Ezra 8:15).

Ahlab.desc: A town in the territory of Asher.

Ai.desc: Ai of Ephraim: A town near Bethel in the territory of Ephraim; probably to be identified with Aiath. After an initial defeat, the Canaanite town was eventually conquered by the Israelites (Joshua 7–8).

Ai.2.desc: Ai of Ammon: A town in the territory of Ammon.

Aiath.desc: A town near Bethel in the territory of Ephraim; also known as Ai.

Aijalon.desc: Aijalon of Dan: A Levitical town in the territory of Dan, assigned to the clan of Kohath. It was later held by the tribe of Benjamin (1 Chronicles 8:13).

Aijalon.2.desc: Aijalon of Zebulun: A town or village in the territory of Zebulun where judge Elon was buried (Judges 12:12).

Ain.desc: Ain near the Sea of Galilee: A town along the eastern border of Canaan near the Sea of Galilee.

Ain.2.desc: Ain of Simeon: A town in the territory of Simeon; possibly En-Rimmon.

Ain.3.desc: Ain of Simeon: A Levitical town in the territory of Simeon and Judah; possibly Ashan.

Akeldama.desc: A field, probably south of the valley of Hinnom outside Jerusalem, which was bought with the money Judas was paid to betray Jesus (Matthew 27:3–8).

Akrabbim.desc: A mountain pass between the southwest corner of the Dead Sea and the wilderness of Zin, on the southern border of the territory of Judah (Joshua 15:3).

Alemeth.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Benjamin; also known as Almon.

Alexandria.desc: A major city in Egypt located on the Mediterranean coast. It was founded by Alexander the Great. The city had a large Jewish population and later became a center of early Christianity.

Allammelech.desc: A town in the territory of Asher.

Allon.desc: An oak tree near Zaanannim that served as a landmark.

Allon-bacuth.desc: An oak tree near Bethel where Deborah, Rebekah's nurse, was buried (Genesis 35:8).

Almon.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Benjamin; also known as Alemeth.

Almon-diblathaim.desc: A location in Moab along the route of the exodus.

Alush.desc: A location in the Sinai Peninsula, between Dophkah and Rephidim, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan.

Amad.desc: A town in the territory of Asher.

Amalek.desc: Amalek Place: The territory in the Negev inhabited by the Amalekites, a nomadic group regarded as descendants of Esau, who were enemies of Israel and ultimately destroyed by Saul (1 Samuel 15:7).

Amam.desc: A town in the territory of Judah.

Amana.desc: A mountain in the Anti-Lebanon range (Song of Songs 4:8).

Amathus.desc: A fortress east of the Jordan River, about halfway between the Sea of Galilee and the Dead Sea; possibly biblical Zaphon.

Amaw.desc: A region near the Euphrates River where Pethor, Balaam's hometown, was located.

Ammah.desc: A hill near Giah on the road to the wilderness of Gihon.

Ammon.desc: A nation located east of the Jordan River. It was founded by Ben-Ammi, son of Lot (Genesis 19:38).

Amphipolis.desc: The capital of southeast Macedonia; Paul and Silas passed through on their way to Thessalonica.

Anab.desc: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah where Joshua eliminated the Anakim (Joshua 11:21).

Anaharath.desc: A town in the territory of Issachar.

Ananiah.desc: Ananiah of Benjamin: A town in the territory of Benjamin.

Anathoth.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Benjamin; home of the prophet Jeremiah.

Anem.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Issachar, assigned to the clan of Gershon; also known as En-Gannim.

Aner.desc: Aner of Manasseh: A Levitical town in the territory of Manasseh.

Angle.desc: A part of the wall of Jerusalem that Uzziah fortified with a tower.

Anim.desc: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah.

Antioch.desc: Antioch of Syria: The capital of the Roman province Syria, located on the Orontes River, where followers of Jesus were first called Christians.

Antioch.2.desc: Antioch of Pisidia: A city in Pisidia, located on the Via Sebaste, where Paul traveled to during his first missionary journey.

Antipatris.desc: A city rebuilt by Herod the Great, east of Joppa; Aphek in the Old Testament.

Aphek.desc: Aphek of Sharon: A town in the Sharon Plain, west of Shiloh; Antipatris in the New Testament.

Aphek.2.desc: Aphek of Asher: A town in the territory of Asher; also known as Aphik.

Aphek.3.desc: Aphek of Aram: A town in Aram (Syria) where Ben-Hadad went to fight against Israel.

Aphek.4.desc: Aphek of Lebanon: A town in Lebanon, which was left unconquered by Joshua (Joshua 13:4).

Aphekah.desc: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah.

Aphik.desc: A town in the territory of Asher; also known as Aphek.

Apollonia.desc: A city in Macedonia located on the Via Egnatia.

Apollonia-Arsuf.desc: An ancient city on the Mediterranean coast, south of Caesarea.

Aquincum.desc: An ancient Roman city in the region of Pannonia, in modern-day Budapest.

Ar.desc: A town in Moab near the Arnon River.

Arab.desc: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah.

Arabah.desc: The deep depression through which the Jordan River flows, which runs from the south of the Sea of Galilee via the Dead Sea into the Gulf of Aqabah.

Arabia.desc: A peninsula located east and south-east of Israel, consisting primarily of steppe and desert and inhabited by nomadic tribes.

Arabia.2.desc: The northwestern Arabian Peninsula, Sinai Peninsula, and the former territory of Nabatea; Paul traveled here after his conversion (Galatians 1:17).

Arad.desc: A Canaanite town located in the Negev, near the wilderness of Judah, conquered by the Israelites.

Aram.desc: A land and ethnic group located in Syria, regarded as descendants of Shem; often referred to as Syria in the Old Testament.

Aram-naharaim.desc: A region in upper Mesopotamia, around the great bend of the Euphrates River in northern Syria; also known as Paddan-Aram. It was the ancestral home of Abraham's family.

Ararat.desc: A mountainous area and nation, also known as Urartu; located in East Asia Minor (ABD); called in a prophecy to punish Babylon.

Arbela.desc: A city in Galilee captured by Demetrius I Soter.

Archelais.desc: A town founded by Herod Archelaus near Jericho.

Areopagus.desc: The location of an Athenian court, traditionally associated with a rocky hill close to the Acropolis, though probably located in the marketplace at the foot of the hill; literally "hill of Mars."

Argob.desc: A region in Bashan taken by the Israelites from the kingdom of Og; assigned to the half-tribe of Manasseh.

Ariel.desc: Another name for the city of Jerusalem.

Arimathea.desc: A city in Judea, northwest of Jerusalem; home to Joseph, who provided a tomb for Jesus after he was crucified (Matthew 27:57–61; Mark 15:42–47; Luke 23:50–56; John 19:38–42).

Armageddon.desc: A cryptic place name designating the territory which will be the scene of the final battle of the forces of good and evil.

Arnon.desc: A river east of the Jordan which constitutes the border between Moab and Ammon.

Aroer.desc: Aroer of Gad: A town situated east of Rabbah in the territory of Gad.

Aroer.2.desc: Aroer of Reuben: A town in the territory of Reuben, located on the rim of the valley of the Arnon River.

Aroer.3.desc: Aroer of Judah: A town in the territory of Judah located to the West of the Jordan River.

Arpad.desc: A town in North Syria, which was conquered by Assyria.

Arubboth.desc: A town in Sharon where Ben-Hasad, one of Solomon's twelve governors, lived (1 Kings 4:10).

Arumah.desc: A town in the territory of Ephraim; possibly to be identified with Rumah or Dumah.

Arvad.desc: A town on a small island off the coast of Phoenicia; its people are considered descendants of Canaan (ABD).

Ashan.desc: A Levitical town in the foothills, in the territory of Judah or Simeon, that received part of the loot that David took on his raids. The exact location is unknown; also known as Bor-Ashan.

Ashdod.desc: A town in Philistia; one of the five cities of the Philistines.

Ashkelon.desc: A town in Philistia; one of the five cities of the Philistines.

Ashkenaz.desc: A nation, probably to be identified with the Scythians, located in the area between the Black Sea and Caspian Sea; considered descendants of a person with the same name. Ashkenaz was called in a prophecy to punish Babylon.

Ashnah.desc: Ashnah Joshua 15:33: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Ashnah.2.desc: Ashnah Joshua 15:43: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Ashtaroth.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Manasseh, east of the Jordan River, assigned to the clan of Gershon; possibly to be identified with Beeshterah, Ashteroth-Karnaim, and Karnaim. It was the former residence of King Sihon of Heshbon and King Og of Bashan and conquered by the Israelites.

Ashteroth-karnaim.desc: A town in Bashan where Chedorlaomer defeated the Rephaim (Genesis 14:5); possibly to be identified with Beeshterah, Ashtaroth and Karnaim.

Asia.desc: The Roman province of Asia, primarily the western part of present-day Turkey.

AsiaMinor.desc: A peninsula in southwestern Asia, modern-day central and western Turkey; several letters in the New Testament are addressed to churches in this region.

Asshur.desc: A city on the Tigris River and first capital of Assyria.

Assos.desc: A seaport city of Mysia where Paul met up with Luke during his third missionary journey.

Assyria.desc: A nation in northern Mesopotamia, with Nineveh as its capital; regarded as descendants of Shem.

Atad.desc: A threshing floor near the Jordan River where Jacob's descendants mourned their father's death.

Ataroth.desc: Ataroth of Gad: A town in the territory of Gad, east of the Jordan River, which was captured from Sihon, king of Heshbon, and Og, king of Bashan.

Ataroth-addar.desc: A border town in the territory of Ephraim, near the territory of Benjamin.

Ataroth.2.desc: Ataroth of Ephraim: A town in the territory of Ephraim; former territory of Arkites.

Athach.desc: A town in the territory of Judah.

Atharim.desc: A location along the route of the exodus where the Israelites were attacked by the king of Arad.

Athens.desc: A principal city of Greece where Paul preached at the Areopagus.

Atroth-beth-joab.desc: A town in the territory of Judah.

Atroth-shophan.desc: A town in the territory of Gad, east of the Jordan River.

labels: City of Augustus in the Land of the Treveri
AugustaTreverorum.desc: A Roman city honoring Caesar Augustus located on the Moselle River; modern-day Trier, Germany.

AugustaVindelicum.desc: A Roman city honoring Caesar Augustus; modern-day Augsburg, Germany.

Aven.desc: A town and cult center in the territory of Ephraim, near the border of Benjamin; normally referred to as Bethel or Beth-Aven. It is probably a pun featuring the meaning of אָוֶן "evil, iniquity" because of the idolatry that was practiced in this town.

AvenValley.desc: A valley mentioned along with Damascus in Amos 1:5; probably to be identified with the Biqah Valley in present-day Lebanon (Andersen/Freedman).

Avith.desc: A town in Edom; residence of Hadad, king of Edom.

Avva.desc: A town, also known as Ivvah; its inhabitants were relocated to Samaria by the king of Assyria (2 Kings 17:24).

Avvim.desc: A town in the territory of Benjamin.

Azal.desc: An unknown location mentioned in Zech 14:5; possibly near Jerusalem.

Azekah.desc: A fortified town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Azmaveth.desc: A location in the territory of Benjamin; also known as Beth-Azmaveth.

Azmon.desc: A village in the territory of Judah.

Aznoth-tabor.desc: A location on the border of the territory of Naphtali.

Baal-gad.desc: A town at the foot of Mount Hermon associated with the worship of the god of Fortune.

Baal-hamon.desc: A location where King Solomon was said to have a vineyard.

Baal-hazor.desc: A location near Ephraim where Absalom had his brother Amnon killed (2 Samuel 13:23–33).

Baal-hermon.desc: A town in the territory of Manasseh near Mount Hermon.

Baal-meon.desc: A town in the territory of Reuben, and later of Moab; also known as Beth-Meon, Beth-Baal-Meon, and Beon.

Baal-perazim.desc: A mountain where King David defeated the Philistines; also known as Mount Perazim.

Baal-shalishah.desc: A town in the territory of Ephraim, probably located in the region of Shalishah.

Baal-tamar.desc: A place between Bethel and Gibeah where the Israelites defeated the Benjamites.

Baal-zephon.desc: A location in eastern Egypt, near the Sea of Reeds and west of Pi-Hahiroth; the Israelites camped near there during the exodus.

Baalah.desc: Baalah in the Negev: A village in the territory of Judah, in the Negev toward the border of Edom.

Baalah.2.desc: Baalah of Judah: A town on the northern border of the territory of Judah; also known as Kiriath-Jearim, Kiriath-Baal, and Baale-Judah.

Baalath.desc: Baalath of Dan: A town in the territory of Dan.

Baalath-beer.desc: A village in the territory of Simeon.

Baalath.2.desc: Baalath of Judah:  A town in the territory of Judah; fortified by Solomon.

Baale-judah.desc: A town in the territory of Judah; also known as Kiriath-Jearim, Kiriath-Baal, and Baalah.

Babel.desc: A town in Mesopotamia founded by Nimrod where the tower of Babel was built; capital of the Chaldean Empire.

Babylon.desc: An ancient city in southern Mesopotamia, located on the Euphrates River; capital of the Babylonian Empire.

Babylon.2.desc: Babylon Symbolic: Traditionally understood as a metaphorical reference to Rome.

Babylonia.desc: A region in southern Mesopotamia through which the Euphrates and Tigris rivers flow.

BacaValley.desc: An unknown location; the name may reflect the "weeping (= dripping)" of balsam trees.

Bahurim.desc: A location east of the Mount of Olives, near Jerusalem, in the territory of Benjamin.

Balah.desc: A town in the territory of Simeon; also known as Bilhah and Baalah.

Bamah.desc: A high place for worship mentioned in Ezekiel 20:29.

Bamoth.desc: A location along the route of the exodus from Egypt to Canaan.

Bamoth-baal.desc: A location in Moab from where Balaam was to curse the Israelites.

Bashan.desc: A region northeast of the Jordan River which was ruled by King Og and later assigned to half of the tribe of Manasseh.

Batanea.desc: A Roman province northeast of the Jordan River; known as Bashan in the Old Testament.

Bath-rabbim.desc: A name of one of the gates of Heshbon, located near a number of pools.

Bealoth.desc: Bealoth of Judah: A town in the territory of Judah; possibly to be identified with Baalath-Beer.

Bealoth.2.desc: Bealoth North of Israel: A town north of Israel where Baana, one of Solomon's twelve governors, lived (1 Kings 4:16).

BeautifulGate.desc: A gate of Herod's Temple in Jerusalem where a lame man was healed by Peter and John (Acts 3:1–10).

Beer.desc: Beer of Moab: A location with a well north of the Arnon River where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan (Numbers 21:16).

Beer-elim.desc: A location in Moab, perhaps in the north, in contrast to Eglaim in the south (Isa 15:8).

Beer-lahai-roi.desc: A well between Kadesh-Barnea and Bered in the Negev, which was named by Hagar after a messenger of God spoke with her; Isaac later settled there.

Beer.2.desc: Beer of Benjamin: A town around ten kilometers north of Jerusalem, in the territory of Benjamin; possibly to be identified with Beeroth.

Beeroth.desc: A town in Lebanon, which was left unconquered by Joshua (Joshua 13:4).

labels: Beeroth of the children of Jaakan
wells of the people of Jaakan
BeerothBene-jaakan.desc: A campsite in the Sinai Peninsula, between Moserah and Hor-Haggidad, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan; also known as Bene-Jaakan.

Beersheba.desc: Beersheba in the Negev: A town located in the Negev, at the southern border of Judah; used especially in combination with Dan at the northern border of Israel to refer to all Israel.

Beersheba.2.desc: A fortified village between Upper and Lower Galilee used during the First Jewish Revolt.

Beeshterah.desc: A Levitical town assigned to the clan of Gershon in the territory of Manasseh, east of the Jordan River; possibly to be identified with Ashtaroth, Ashteroth-Karnaim, and Karnaim.

Bene-berak.desc: A town in the territory of Dan.

labels: Beeroth of the children of Jaakan
Bene-jaakan.desc: A location in the Sinai Peninsula, between Moseroth and Hor-Haggidgad, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan.

BenjaminGate.desc: A gate in the wall of Jerusalem through which the prophet Jeremiah tried to leave the city (Jer 37:12–13).

Beon.desc: A town in the territory of Reuben, and later of Moab; also known as Beth-Meon, Beth-Baal-Meon, and Baal-Meon.

BeracahValley.desc: A valley near Tekoa where King Jehoshaphat and his people gathered to bless Yahweh for their victory over a coalition of invading Moabites, Ammonites, Edomites, and Meunites (ABD).

Berea.desc: A city in Macedonia where Paul and Silas traveled to after being driven out of Thessalonica.

Bered.desc: Bered Place: A location near Kadesh; probably with cold water.

Berothah.desc: A town on the northern border of the land of Israel, according to the vision of the prophet Ezekiel (Ezekiel 47:16); perhaps to be identified with Berothai.

Berothai.desc: A town in the territory of Hadadezer, king of Zobah.

Besor.desc: A stream in the territory of the Philistines where some of David's men rested while the rest continued their pursuit of those who raided Ziklag (1 Samuel 30:9–10).

Beten.desc: A town in the territory of Asher.

Beth-anath.desc: A fortified town in the territory of Naphtali.

Beth-anoth.desc: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah.

Beth-arabah.desc: A town in the wilderness on the boundary between the territories of Judah and Benjamin.

Beth-arbel.desc: A town in Galilee destroyed by Shalman (Hos 10:14).

Beth-ashbea.desc: A town inhabited by descendants of Judah, known for their production of linen.

Beth-aven.desc: Beth-aven of Benjamin: A town in the territory of Benjamin, near Ai and Bethel.

Beth-aven.2.desc: Beth-aven of Ephraim: A town in the territory Of Ephraim; probably a pun or word-play on the name Bethel ("house of God").

Beth-barah.desc: A location close to the Jordan River where the men of Ephraim confronted the Midianites.

Beth-biri.desc: A town in the territory of Simeon until the reign of King David.

Beth-car.desc: A location in the territory of Judah toward which the Israelites pursued the Philistines.

Beth-dagon.desc: Beth-dagon of Judah: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Beth-dagon.2.desc: Beth-dagon of Asher: A town in the territory of Asher.

Beth-diblathaim.desc: A town in the region of Moab; probably to be identified with Almon Diblataim.

Beth-eked.desc: A location between Jezreel and Samaria where Jehu's men killed the relatives of Ahazaiah.

Beth-emek.desc: A town in the territory of Asher.

Beth-ezel.desc: A town in the territory of Judah. The name is probably a pun on the Hebrew אצל (English: withhold).

Beth-gader.desc: A town in the territory of Judah; probably to be identified with Geder.

Beth-gamul.desc: A town in the region of Moab upon which Jeremiah pronounced judgment (Jer 48:23).

Beth-gilgal.desc: A town near Jerusalem from which singers came after exile to dedicate the rebuilt walls of Jerusalem (Nehemiah 12:27–30).

Beth-haccherem.desc: A town in the territory of Judah or Benjamin, close to Jerusalem, ruled by Malchijah.

Beth-haggan.desc: A town toward which King Ahaziah of Judah fled from King Jehu of Israel (2 Kings 9:27).

Beth-haram.desc: A town in the territory of Gad.

Beth-hoglah.desc: A town on the northern border of the territory of Benjamin.

Beth-horonLower.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Ephraim; assigned to the clan of Kohath.

Beth-horonUpper.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Ephraim; assigned to the clan of Kohath.

Beth-jeshimoth.desc: A town in the region of Moab allotted to the tribe of Reuben.

Beth-lebaoth.desc: A town in the territory of Simeon; also known as Lebaoth.

Beth-marcaboth.desc: A town in the territory of Simeon.

Beth-meon.desc: A town in the territory of Reuben, and later of Moab; also known as Beth-Baal-Meon, Baal-Meon, and Beon.

labels: a place that was far off

Beth-millo.desc: A location near or in Shechem where Abimelech was crowned king.

Beth-nimrah.desc: A town in the territory of Gad; also known as Nimrah.

Beth-pazzez.desc: A town in the territory of Issachar.

Beth-pelet.desc: A town in the territory of Judah

Beth-peor.desc: A town in Moab allotted to the tribe of Reuben, near where Moses introduced the Law to the Israelites.

Beth-rehob.desc: A town near Sidon on the border between Dan and Syria.

Beth-shan.desc: A border town in the territory of West Manasseh, near Zarethan, where Saul's body was hung after he was killed.

Beth-shemesh.desc: Beth-shemesh of Judah: A Levitical town in the territory of Judah, assigned to the clan of Aaron.

Beth-shemesh.2.desc: Beth-shemesh of Issachar: A town in the territory of Issachar.

Beth-shemesh.3.desc: Beth-shemesh of Naphtali: A fortified town in the territory of Naphtali.

Beth-shittah.desc: A town northeast of Beth-Shean to which the Midianite army fled (Judges 7:22).

Beth-tappuah.desc: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah.

Beth-togarmah.desc: A nation located north of Israel and regarded as founded by a person with the same name; renowned for its horses and mules.

Beth-zur.desc: A town in the territory of Judah fortified by Rehoboam; ruled by Nehemiah, son of Azbuk.

Bethabara.desc: A place on the east side of the Jordan River where John baptized.

Bethany.desc: Bethany on the Mount of Olives: A village on the Mount of Olives, where Mary, Martha, and Lazarus lived (John 11:1).

Bethel.desc: Bethel of Ephraim: A town and cult center in the territory of Ephraim, near the border of Benjamin; also referred to as Beth-Aven, or simply Aven.

Bethel.2.desc: Bethel of Simeon: A town in the territory of Simeon; also known as Bethul and Bethuel.

BetherMountain.desc: Bether Song of Solomon 2:17: A craggy area mentioned in Song 2:17; possibly not a reference to a proper name.

Bethesda.desc: A pool in Jerusalem where people came to be healed; Jesus healed a man who has been an invalid for 38 years there.

Bethlehem.desc: Bethlehem of Judah: A town in the territory of Judah, southwest of Jerusalem, where Jesus was born; ancestral town of King David.

Bethlehem.2.desc: Bethlehem of Zebulun: A town in the territory of Zebulun, where the judge Ibzan was born and died.

Bethphage.desc: A village east of Bethany (on the Mount of Olives), where Jesus sent two of his disciples to retrieve a donkey for him to ride upon as he entered Jerusalem (Matthew 21:1–11; Mark 11:1–11; Luke 19:28–40).

Bethsaida.desc: A town northeast of the Sea of Galilee; hometown of Peter, Andrew, and Philip (John 1:44).

Bethuel.desc: A town in the territory of Simeon; also known as Bethu and Bethel.

Bethul.desc: A town in the territory of Simeon; also known as Bethuel and Bethel.

Betonim.desc: A town east of the Jordan River in the territory of Gad.

BeyondTheJordan.desc: A region east of the Jordan River.

Bezek.desc: Bezek of Manasseh: A town in the territory of Manasseh, where the Israelites struck down 10,000 Canaanites and Perizzites (Judges 1:4).

Bezer.desc: A Levitical town of refuge in the wilderness in the territory of Reuben, assigned to the clan of Merari.

Bileam.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Manasseh, assigned to the clan of the Kohathites; probably to be identified with Ibleam.

Bilhah.desc: A town in the territory of Simeon; also known as Balah, Baalah, and Baaloth.

Bithynia.desc: A province in northern Asia Minor; Paul, Silas, and Timothy tried to enter while traveling through the province of Asia, but were not permitted by the Spirit of Jesus (Acts 16:7).

Biziothiah.desc: A town in the southern territory of Judah.

Bochim.desc: A location near Gilgal where the Angel of the Lord appeared to the Israelites after the conquest of the promised land.

Bor-ashan.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Judah or Simeon which received part of the loot that David took on his raids (1 Samuel 30:30); also known as Ashan. The exact location is unknown.

Bostra.desc: A city in Gilead, east of the Decapolis, captured by Judas Maccabeus (1 Maccabees 5:28).

Bozez.desc: A steep rock face near Michmash, facing another rock named Seneh.

Bozkath.desc: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah; home of Jedidah, mother of Josiah.

Bozrah.desc: Bozrah of Moab: A city in Moab mentioned in Jer 48:24.

Bozrah.2.desc: Bozrah of Edom: The capital of Edom.

BrookOfEgypt.desc: A river on the southwest border of Israel.

BrookOfTheWillows.desc: A brook marking the boundary between Moab and Edom; possibly the Brook Zered.

Brundisium.desc: A Roman port city in southern Italy; modern-day Brindisi.

Burdigala.desc: A Roman city in southwest France; modern-day Bordeaux.

Buz.desc: Buz Nation: A nation in North Arabia.

Byzantium.desc: A Greek city at the southern end of the Bosphorus; modern-day Istanbul. In 330, Emperor Constantine moved the capital of the Roman Empire here and renamed the city Constantinople.

Cabbon.desc: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Cabul.desc: Cabul of Asher: A town in the territory of Asher.

Cabul.2.desc: Cabul of Galilee: A region in Galilee given to Hiram king of Tyre by Solomon (1 Kings 9:13).

Caesarea.desc: A seaport on the coast of Palestine, south of Mount Carmel; home of Philip the evangelist.

Caesarea.2.desc: Caesarea of Cappadocia: The capital city of Cappadocia; modern-day Kayseri, Turkey.

CaesareaPhilippi.desc: A city at the foot of Mount Hermon, where Peter makes his confession of Christ (Matthew 16:13–20; Mark 8:27–30)

Calah.desc: A town in Mesopotamia built by Nimrod after the flood.

CalebEphrathah.desc: The place where Caleb's father, Hezron, died; possibly not a place but a person.

Calneh.desc: A town in Syria near Arpad and Aleppo (ABD).

Cana.desc: A city in Galilee where Jesus turned water into wine; home of Jesus' disciple Nathanael.

Canaan.desc: The region in the southern Levant inhabited by people who were regarded as descendants of Canaan, son of Ham, son of Noah; settled by Abraham.

Canneh.desc: A town in Mesopotamia that traded with Tyre (Ezekiel 27:23).

Capernaum.desc: A city on the northwest coast of the Sea of Galilee. After leaving Nazareth, Jesus moved here where he did much of his ministry.

Caphtor.desc: The land of origin of the Philistines; probably to be identified with Crete.

Cappadocia.desc: A province in the interior of Asia Minor; some of the crowd who were at Pentecost were from here (Acts 2:5–13).

Carchemish.desc: A town on the Euphrates River where Nebuchadnezzar defeated the Assyrians and the Egyptians (Jer 46:1–2).

Carmel.desc: Carmel of Judah: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah.

CarmelMount.desc: A coastal mountain range in northern Israel, west of the Jezreel Valley, where the prophet Elijah confronted the prophets of Baal (1 Kings 18:16–35).

Carthage.desc: An ancient seaport city on the northern coast of Africa.

Casiphia.desc: A location in Babylonia where temple servants were living while in exile.

Cauda.desc: A small island south of Crete which Paul passed on his voyage to Rome, prior to the shipwreck.

Cenchreae.desc: A seaport of the city of Corinth; home of Phoebe who was a servant of the church there.

Chalcedon.desc: A maritime city in the province of Bithynia, Asia Minor. Several church councils were held here, including the Fourth Ecumenical Council, the Council of Chalcedon, in 451.

Chaldea.desc: The land in lower Mesopotamia inhabited by the descendants of Chesed, son of Nahor.

Chebar.desc: A river in Babylonia where Ezekiel received one of his visions while in exile (Ezekiel 1:1).

Chephar-ammoni.desc: A city in the territory of Benjamin.

Chephirah.desc: A town in the territory of Benjamin; one of the four Hivite cities that made a covenant with Joshua (Joshua 9:17–18).

Cherith.desc: A wadi east of the Jordan River where the prophet Elijah hid from king Ahab and was fed by ravens (1KI 17:2–7).

Cherub.desc: A town in Babylon from which a group of Jews return to Israel (Ezra 2:59; Nehemiah 7:61).

Chesalon.desc: A town in the territory of Judah near Mount Jearim.

Chesil.desc: A town in the southern territory of Judah, near the border of Edom.

Chesulloth.desc: A town in the territory of Issachar; also known as Chisloth-Tabor.

Chezib.desc: The place where Shua, wife of Judah, gave birth to her son Shelah.

Chilmad.desc: A town, possibly in Mesopotamia, that traded with Tyre (Ezekiel 27:23).

Chinnereth.desc: A town in the territory of Naphtali at the Sea of Galilee.

Chios.desc: An island, with a city of the same name, in the Aegean Sea; Paul and his companions passed the island while traveling to Jerusalem.

Chisloth-tabor.desc: A town in the territory of Issachar; also known as Chesulloth.

Chitlish.desc: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Chorazin.desc: A city in Galilee on which Jesus pronounced woe due to its inhabitants lack of repentance.

Cilicia.desc: A province in the southeast corner of Asia Minor; Paul was from Tarsus, the capital city of the province, and traveled through the region during his second missionary journey.

CityOfDavid.desc: The oldest part of Jerusalem, east of the Old City and south of the temple mount, where David captured and renamed a Jebusite fortress (2 Samuel 5:6-11); not to be confused with Bethlehem, which is also referred to as the City of David (Luke 2:11).

CityOfDestruction.desc: An Egyptian city referenced in Isa 19:18; possibly a reference to the city of Heliopolis.

CityOfPalms.desc: A city in the territory of Judah; also known as Jericho.

CityOfPalms.2.desc: A town in the territory of Judah; also known as Jericho.

CityOfSalt.desc: A town in the wilderness of the territory of Judah.

Cnidus.desc: A seaport on the southwest coast of Asia Minor; Paul and his companions stopped here during the voyage to Rome, prior to encountering the storm at sea.

Colossae.desc: A city in Phrygia in Asia Minor near Hierapolis and Laodicea; the letter to the Colossians was addressed to the church there.

Corduba.desc: The capital city of the Roman province Hispania Ulterior located on the southern Iberian Peninsula; modern-day Córdoba, Spain.

Corinth.desc: A city in Greece where Paul ministered for a year and a half (Acts 18:11); Paul wrote at least two letters to the church here.

CornerGate.desc: A gate in the wall of Jerusalem which Jehoash destroyed (2 Kings 14:13; 2 Chronicles25:23); later Uzziah built towers there (2 Chronicles26:9).

Cos.desc: An island in the Aegean Sea where Paul's ship made a stop on his journey to Jerusalem.

Cozeba.desc: A location in the territory of Judah.

Crete.desc: An island in the Mediterranean Sea, south of Greece, where Titus ministered (Tit 1:5).

Ctesiphon.desc: A city in Mesopotamia on the east bank of the Tigris River, southeast of modern-day Baghdad, Iraq. It was the capital of the Parthian and Sasanian empires.

Cun.desc: A town in the territory of King Hadadezer of Zobah which was a major source of bronze during the time of King David (1 Chronicles 18:8).

Cush.desc: Cush near Gihon: A region of uncertain location, through which the Gihon flows (Genesis 2:13).

Cush.2.desc: Cush Nation: An ethnic group and their territory; regarded as descendants of Cush, son of Ham.

Cushan.desc: A land or ethnic group, possibly related to Midian.

Cuth.desc: A town in northern Babylonia; its inhabitants were relocated to Samaria by the king of Assyria.

Cyprus.desc: An island off the south coast of Asia Minor; Paul and Barnabas ministered here during Paul's first missionary journey (Acts 13:4–12).

Cyrene.desc: A city on the coast of North Africa and its people; home of Simon, who was forced to carry the cross of Christ (Matthew 27:32–44).

Dabbesheth.desc: A town in the territory of Zebulun.

Daberath.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Issachar, assigned to the clan of Gershon.

Dalmanutha.desc: A place of uncertain location near the western shore of the Sea of Galilee, where Jesus went after feeding the 4,000 (Mark 8:10); possibly another name for Magadan.

Damascus.desc: A town in Syria; capital of one of the Aramaean kingdoms. Paul was converted on the road to Damascus (Acts 9:1–9).

Dan.desc: A town in northern Israel first inhabited by Sidonians, but later conquered by Danites, who renamed it Dan after the founder of their tribe; also known as Laish and Leshem.

Dannah.desc: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah.

Daphne.desc: A town near Antioch on the Orontes.

Debir.desc: Debir of Judah: A Levitical town in the hill country of the territory of Judah, assigned to the clan of Aaron; formerly called Kiriath-Sepher and also known as Kiriath-Sannah. It was captured by Othniel, Israel's first judge (Judges 1:11–13).

Debir.2.desc: Debir above Achor Valley: A town of the territory of Judah that marks the northern boundary of the territory.

Decapolis.desc: A league of ten cities in a region southeast of the Sea of Galilee, where Jesus healed a deaf man (Matthew 27:31–37; Mark 15:21–32).

Dedan.desc: A location in the Arabian Peninsula; home of an ethnic group with the same name.

Derbe.desc: A city in Lycaonia, southeast of Lystra; Paul ministered here during his missionary journeys.

Dibon.desc: Dibon of Moab: A town in Moab said to be built by the tribe of Gad, but also attributed to the tribe of Reuben.

Dibon.2.desc: Dibon of Judah: A town in the territory of Judah; probably to be identified with Dimonah.

Dibon.3.desc: Dimon of Moab: A town in Moab mentioned in Isaiah 15:9.

Dilean.desc: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Dimnah.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Zebulun assigned to the clan of Merari.

Dimonah.desc: A town in the southern territory of Judah, near the border of Edom; probably to be identified with Dibon.

Dinhabah.desc: A town in Edom ruled by Bela, son of Beor.

Dizahab.desc: A location in the Arabah, not far from the place where Moses repeated the law.

Dophkah.desc: A location in the Sinai Peninsula between the wilderness of Sin and Alush, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan.

Dor.desc: A coastal town in the territory of West Manasseh, north of Caesarea.

Dothan.desc: A town in northern Israel, probably to be identified with Tel Dothan; Joseph went to meet his brothers there before they plotted to kill him (Genesis 37:17).

DragonSpring.desc: A spring outside Jerusalem between the Valley Gate and the Dung Gate.

Dumah.desc: Dumah of Arabia: A region in north-central Arabia, inhabited by an ethnic group that were regarded as descendants of Dumah, the son of Ishmael, the son of Abraham.

Dumah.2.desc: Dumah of Judah: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah; possibly to be identified with Arumah.

DungGate.desc: A gate in the wall of Jerusalem in the time of Nehemiah.

Dura.desc: A plain in Babylon where Nebuchadnezzar set up a large, golden image (Dan 3:1).

EastGate.desc: A gate in the city of Jerusalem.

EbalMount.desc: A mountain north of Shechem where the Israelites pronounced curses (Deuteronomy 11:29); often associated with Mount Gerizim to the south.

Ebenezer.desc: Ebenezer Place: A location near Aphek where the Israelites encamped before battling the Philistines (1 Samuel 4:1).

Ebenezer.2.desc: Ebenezer Monument: A rock erected by Samuel as a memorial between Mizpah and Shen.

Ebez.desc: A town in the territory of Issachar.

Ebron.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Asher, assigned to the clan of Gershon; also known as Abdon.

Eburacum.desc: A city in the Roman province of Britannia; modern-day York.

Ecbatana.desc: The capital city of the province of Media, where a scroll containing the decrees of King Darius were found (Ezra 6).

Eden.desc: Eden of Mesopotamia: A region in northern Mesopotamia.

Eden.2.desc: A location in the east where God planted the garden in which he placed the first man and woman, until they were sent away; often used to denote the garden itself; associated with joy, fertility, and prosperity.

Eder.desc: Eder of Judah: A town in southern Judah near the border with Edom, belonging to the tribe of Judah.

Edessa.desc: A city in Mesopotamia, east of the Euphrates River, which was a major center for early Christianity.

Edom.desc: A nation located south of the Dead Sea; considered descendants of Esau.

Edrei.desc: Edrei of Og: A town in Bashan; part of the kingdom of Og, and later assigned to Manasseh.

Edrei.2.desc: Edrei of Naphtali: A fortified town in the territory of Naphtali.

Eglaim.desc: A town in Moab mentioned in Isa 15:8.

Eglon.desc: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah captured by Joshua (Joshua 10:35).

Egypt.desc: A nation and their territory; regarded as founded by one of the sons of Ham with the same name.

EgyptSea.desc: Possibly a reference to the Red Sea which is shaped like a tongue; literally "sea of Egypt."

Ekron.desc: A town in Philistia; one of the five cities of the Philistines.

El-paran.desc: A location on the edge of the wilderness up to where Kedorlaomer defeated the Horites; probably to be identified with Elath (ABD).

ElahValley.desc: A valley in the Shephelah where David killed Goliath (1 Samuel 17).

Elam.desc: A nation located between Mesopotamia and Persia; regarded as founded by a person with the same name.

Elath.desc: A seaport at the northern tip of the northeastern projection of the Red Sea, in Edom.

Elealeh.desc: A town in the territory of Reuben.

Elim.desc: A location in the Sinai Peninsula, not far from the Sea of Reeds, containing 12 springs of water and 70 palm trees; the Israelites encamped their on their way from Egypt to Canaan.

Elishah.desc: An island known for trading dyed cloth with Tyre; possibly another name for Cyprus.

Ellasar.desc: A region, the location of which is unknown, ruled by Arioch, who joined Chedorlaomer and two other kings to launch a campaign into Canaan.

Elon.desc: A town or village in the territory of Dan.

Elonbeth-hanan.desc: A town during the time of King Solomon under control of Ben-Deker.

Eltekeh.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Dan, assigned to the clan of Kohath.

Eltekon.desc: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah.

Eltolad.desc: A town in the territory of Simeon; also known as Tolad.

Emek-keziz.desc: A town in the territory of Benjamin.

Emmatha.desc: A town northwest of Gadara; modern-day Hamat Gader.

Emmaus.desc: A village in Judea, not far from Jerusalem, where Jesus appeared to two disciples after his resurrection (Luke 24:13–35).

En-dor.desc: A town in the territory of Issachar but allotted to Manasseh, where Saul consulted with a medium (1 Samuel 28:7–25).

En-gannim.desc: En-gannim of Judah: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

En-gannim.2.desc: En-gannim of Issachar: A Levitical town in the territory of Issachar, assigned to the clan of Gershon; also known as Anem.

En-haddah.desc: A town in the territory of Issachar.

labels: The Spring of the One Who Cried Out
En-hakkore.desc: A spring at Lehi from which Samson drank.

En-hazor.desc: A fortified town in the territory of Naphtali.

En-rimmon.desc: A town in the territory of Judah, and later Simeon.

En-rogel.desc: A spring on the boundary between the territories of Judah and Benjamin.

En-shemesh.desc: A spring on the border between the territories of Judah and Benjamin.

En-tappuah.desc: A spring on the boundary between the territories of Judah and Benjamin.

Enaim.desc: A town on the way to Timnah, in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Enam.desc: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah/

Eneglaim.desc: A spring near the Dead Sea.

Engedi.desc: An oasis in the wilderness of the territory of Judah, on the western shore of the Dead Sea; also known as Hazezon-Tamar.

Ephes-dammim.desc: A location between Socoh and Azekah, in the territory of Judah, where the Philistines encamped during the battle between David and Goliath; also known as Pas-Dammim.

Ephesus.desc: A seaport in the western part of the Roman province of Asia; one of the seven cities addressed in Revelation. The letter of Ephesians was addressed to the church there.

Ephraim.desc: Ephraim near Baal-hazor: A town near Baal-Hazor, where Absalom took revenge on Ammon.

Ephraim.2.desc: Ephraim near the Wilderness: A city of uncertain location near the wilderness, visited by Jesus.

EphraimGate.desc: A gate in the wall of Jerusalem which Jehoash destroyed (2 Kings 14:13).

EphraimMount.desc: A mountainous region in the territory of Ephraim.

Ephrath.desc: A town in the territory of Judah where Jacob buried Rachel, his wife; also known as Ephrathah and Bethlehem.

Ephrathah.desc: A town in the territory of Judah where Jacob buried Rachel, his wife; also known as Ephrath and Bethlehem.

Ephron.1.desc: Ephron Joshua 18:15: A settlement on the border between Benjamin and Judah; possibly meaning "westward."

Ephron.2.desc: A town on the boundary between the territories of Ephraim and Benjamin; also known as Ephron; captured by Abijah, king of Judah, from Jeroboam I, king of Israel.

EphronMount.desc: A mountain near the boundary of the territory of Judah.

Erech.desc: A town near the East bank of the Euphrates on a subsidiary of that river (ABD).

Esek.desc: A well dug by herdsmen of Isaac, which became a source of contention between them and the herdsmen of Gerar.

Eshan.desc: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah.

EshcolValley.desc: A valley near Hebron where Israelite spies cut off a large cluster of grapes (Numbers 13:23–24).

Eshtaol.desc: A town in the foothills of the territory of Dan, near where Samson was buried.

Eshtemoa.desc: A Levitical town in the hill country of the territory of Judah, assigned to the clan of Aaron; also known as Eshtemoh.

Etam.desc: Etam of Judah: A town in the territory of Judah; regarded as founded by a man with the same name.

Etam.2.desc: Etam of Simeon: A village in the territory of Simeon.

Etam.4.desc: A location with a cave where Samson stayed after striking down the Philistines (Judges 15:8).

Eth-kazin.desc: A town in the territory of Zebulun.

Etham.desc: A location in eastern Egypt near Succoth and on the edge of the desert, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan. When setting out from Etham they turned back in the direction of Pi-Hahiroth, and after having crossed the Sea of Reeds the Israelites passed through the desert of Etham.

Ether.desc: Ether of Judah: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Ether.2.desc: Ether of Simeon: A town in the territory of Simeon.

Ethiopia.desc: A country south of Egypt; approximately equivalent to Cush.

Euphrates.desc: A large river in Mesopotamia; one of the four rivers flowing from the garden of Eden.

EzelStone.desc: A stone where David and Jonathan met before David left Saul's court.

Ezem.desc: A town in the territory of Judah and later assigned to Simeon.

Ezion-geber.desc: A seaport town on the Gulf of Aqaba, near Elath, where the Israelites camped on their journey from Egypt to Canaan.

FairHavens.desc: A bay on the south coast of Crete; Paul's ship sought refuge from the windy sea on his voyage to Rome.

FishGate.desc: A gate in the northern wall of Jerusalem.

ForestEphraim.desc: A forest where Absalom was killed following a battle against David's army.

ForumOfAppius.desc: A market town south of Rome which Paul visited on his way to Rome.

FoundationGate.desc: A gate in Jerusalem, possibly leading from the royal palace to the temple; another name for the Gate of Sur.

FountainGate.desc: A gate of Jerusalem in the City of David.

Gaash.desc: A mountainous region in the hill country of Ephraim

Gabbatha.desc: The Aramaic name for a paved area outside the residence of Pontius Pilate and the setting for the public trial of Jesus.

Gadara.desc: Gadara of the Decapolis: A Decapolis city southwest of the Sea of Galilee; modern-day Umm Qais.

Gadara.2.desc: Gadara of Perea: The capital city of the province of Perea, southwest of modern-day As-Salt, Jordan.

Gades.desc: A city in Spain on the southwest Iberian Peninsula; modern-day Cádiz.

Galatia.desc: A district in the Roman province of Asia; the letter to the Galatians is addressed to the church here.

Galilee.desc: A region located in the northernmost part of Israel where most of Jesus' ministry took place.

GalileeSea.desc: A large body of freshwater east of the territory of Galilee, in northern Israel, through which the Jordan River flows and where Jesus walked on water (Matthew 14:22–33; Mark 6:45–52; John 6:16–21).

Gallim.desc: A location in the territory of Benjamin, north of Jerusalem.

Gamad.desc: A town east-northeast of sidon; possibly to be identified with Kumidi of the El-Amarna letters.

Gamala.desc: An ancient Jewish city in the Golan Heights.

Gareb.desc: A hill in the immediate vicinity of Jerusalem; possibly north or west of the city.

Gath.desc: A town in Philistia; one of the five cities of the Philistines.

Gath-hepher.desc: A town in the territory of Zebulun; home town of the prophet Jonah.

Gath-rimmon.desc: Gath-rimmon of Dan: A Levitical town in the territory of Dan, assigned to the clan of Koath.

Gath-rimmon.2.desc: Gath-rimmon of Manasseh: A Levitical town in the territory of Manasseh, west of the Jordan River.

Gaza.desc: A town in Philistia; one of the five cities of the Philistines.

Ge-harashim.desc: A location on the coastal plain, where craftsmen settled; founded by a man named Joab, son of Seraiah, of the tribe of Judah.

Geba.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Benjamin, possibly to be identified with Gibeah; hometown of King Saul.

Gebal.desc: Gebal Byblos: A town in Phoenicia, north of Israel, and functioning as the seaport of the major city of Byblos, which used to trade with Tyre.

Gebal.2.desc: Gebal Nation: An ethnic group or nation located in Transjordan, probably southeast of Dead Sea, near Petra; probably to be identified with the Arabic clan Jibal.

Gebim.desc: A location mentioned in Isa 10:31, probably a few miles north of Jerusalem.

Geder.desc: A town in the territory of Judah, conquered by Joshua and the Israelites; probably to be identified with Beth-Gader.

Gederah.desc: Gederah of Judah: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Gederah.2.desc: Gederah Home of Jozabad: Home of Jozabad the Benjamite; possibly the same as Gederah in the territory of Judah.

Gederoth.desc: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah, conquered and occupied by the Philistines.

Gederothaim.desc: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah; possibly identical to Gederah.

Gedor.desc: Gedor of Judah: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah; founded by Penuel.

Gedor.2.desc: Gedor of Simeon: A town in the territory of Simeon.

Gedor.3.desc: Gedor of Jered: A town in the territory of Judah which was founded by Jered.

Gedor.4.desc: Gedor of Benjamin: A town in the territory of Benjamin.

Geliloth.desc: A location in the territory of Benjamin; also known as Gilgal.

Geneva.desc: A city in southwest Switzerland occupied by the Romans in the first century AD. It was a center of the Protestant Reformation in the sixteenth century.

Gennesaret.desc: A fertile plain on the northwest shore of the Sea of Galilee, south of Capernaum, where Jesus healed many sick people (Matthew 14:34–36; Mark 6:53–56).

Gerar.desc: A town in western Negev, not far from Gaza, inhabited by the Philistines; one of the places where Abraham and Isaac sojourned.

Gerasa.desc: A city in Perea, east of the Jordan and southeast of the Sea of Galilee; one of the cities of the Decapolis. Jesus cast out many demons from a man while in the region near there (Mark 5:1–20; Luke 8:26–39).

GerizimMount.desc: A mountain southwest of Shechem where the Israelites pronounced blessings (Deuteronomy 11:29); often associated with Mount Ebal to the north.

GeruthChimham.desc: A location near Bethlehem where the Judeans, who were on their way to Egypt in the time of Jeremiah, broke their journey.

Geshur.desc: A kingdom located between Gilead, Bashan, and Mount Hermon (ABD).

Gethsemane.desc: A garden at the foot of the Mount of Olives, where Jesus was arrested (Matthew 26:47–56; Mark 14:43–52).

Gezer.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Ephraim, assigned to the clan of Kohath; possibly to be identified with Gob. It was conquered by Joshua and the Israelites but later retaken by the Canaanites.

Giah.desc: A location on the way to the wilderness of Gibeon.

Gibbethon.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Dan, assigned to the clan of Kohath; later controlled by the Philistines. King Nadab, son of Jeroboam, of the northern tribes of Israel, was killed there by Baasha, who succeeded him as king (1Ki 15:27–28).

Gibeah.desc: Gibeah of Judah: A town located in the hilly country of the territory of Judah.

Gibeah.1.desc: Gibeah of Benjamin: The hometown of King Saul, in the territory of Benjamin, where someone's concubine was raped by a large group of men (Judges 20:4–7); possibly to be identified with Geba.

Gibeah.2.desc: Gibeah of Phinehas: A hill or town in the hill country of Ephraim were Eleazar, son of Aaron, was buried.

Gibeath-elohim.desc: A location in the territory of Benjamin where Saul met a group of prophets and prophesied with them; probably to be identified with the town of Gibeah or Geba; exact meaning unsure.

Gibeath-haaraloth.desc: A hill near Jericho where Joshua circumcised the Israelites; literally "hill of the foreskins."

Gibeon.desc: A town in the territory of Benjamin; one of the four Hivite cities that made a covenant with Joshua (Joshua 9:17–18).

Gidom.desc: A location in the territory of Benjamin where Israel struck down 2,000 Benjamites.

Gihon.desc: Gihon of Eden: A river running through the land of Cush; one of the four rivers flowing from the Garden of Eden.

Gihon.2.desc: A spring on the east side of Jerusalem, right outside the city wall; it was later made accessible from inside the town by means of a tunnel.

GilboaMount.desc: A mountain range in Israel, southeast of the Jezreel Valley, where Saul and three of his sons died (1 Samuel 31:1–6).

Gilead.desc: An area on the east side of the Jordan River; supposedly named after Gilead, son of Makir, tribe of Manasseh.

Gilgal.desc: Gilgal of Goiim: A region or town in northern Canaan; possibly another name for Galilee.

Gilgal.2.desc: Gilgal near Shechem: A location close to Shechem and the Oak of Moreh.

Gilgal.3.desc: Gilgal near Jericho: A town close to Jericho where the Israelites first camped after crossing the Jordan River and set up twelve stones as a monument; it later became the location of a cultic center.

Gilgal.4.desc: Gilgal of Judah: A location near the northern boundary of the territory of Judah; also known as Geliloth.

Giloh.desc: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah; hometown of Ahithophel, counselor of David (2 Samuel 15:12).

Gimzo.desc: A town captured by the Philistines in the days of King Ahaz; modern Jimzu, 24 kilometers east-southeast of Joppa.

Gischala.desc: A village in Upper Galilee, northwest of the Sea of Galilee; home to John ben Levi of Giscala, a leader in the First Jewish Revolt.

Gittaim.desc: A town in the territory of Benjamin, where the Beerothites found refuge (2 Samuel 4:2–3).

Goah.desc: A hill near Jerusalem associated with Jeremiah's vision of the restored Jerusalem.

Gob.desc: A town where David fought the Philistines; possibly to be identified with Gezer.

Gog.desc: A cryptic name to designate an enemy to be conquered by the Messiah (Revelation 20:8).

Goiim.1.desc: Goiim of Tidal: An area ruled by Tidal, who joined Chedorlaomer and two other kings to launch a campaign into Canaan; location unknown.

Goiim.2.desc: Goiim in Galilee: An unidentified nation whose king was defeated by Joshua (Joshua 12:23).

Golan.desc: A Levitical town of refuge in Bashan, in the territory of Manasseh east of the Jordan River, assigned to the clan of Gershon.

Golgotha.desc: A hill near Jerusalem where executions took place and where Jesus was crucified (Matthew 27:33–44; Mark 15:21–32; John 19:16–19).

Gomer.desc: A nation located in the vicinity of the Black Sea; possibly to be identified with Cimmerians, considered descendants of Japheth through his son Gomer (Genesis 10:2).

Gomorrah.desc: A town near the Dead Sea that was destroyed with Sodom.

Goshen.desc: Goshen of Egypt: A region in the eastern Egyptian delta where the Israelites lived from the time they settled in the country until the exodus.

Goshen.2.desc: Goshen of Judah: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah.

Goshen.3.desc: A region on the southern border of Israelite territory; conquered by Joshua.

Gozan.desc: A town along the Habor River in Assyria; one of the places where the exiles from Samaria were relocated.

GreatSea.desc: A large body of water located between southern Europe, northern Africa, and western Asia, which borders Palestine on the west.

Greece.desc: A nation on the southern end of the Balkan Peninsula.

Gur.desc: The ascent in the territory of Manasseh, near Ibleam, where Jehu killed Ahaziah.

Gurbaal.desc: A town in Arab territory conquered by Uzziah, king of Judah.

Habor.desc: A river in Mesopotamia; eastern tributary of the Euphrates.

Hachilah.desc: A hill in the territory of Judah.

Hadad-rimmon.desc: A deity worshipped by Arameans, whose death was ritually mourned by his followers; possibly the name of a place in the plain of Megiddo.

Hadashah.desc: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Hadid.desc: A village in the territory of Benjamin.

Hadrach.desc: A town or area in Syria mentioned in Zech 9:1.

Haeleph.desc: A town in the territory of Benjamin.

Hakkephirim.desc: A location in the valley of Ono where Nehemiah was to meet Sanballat and Geshem.

Halah.desc: A location along the Habor River in Assyria; one of the places where the exiles from Samaria were relocated.

HalakMount.desc: A mountain marking the southern boundary of Joshua's conquests (Joshua 11:17); possibly Jebel Halaq.

Halhul.desc: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah.

Hali.desc: A town in the territory of Asher.

HallOfJudgment.desc: A building in Solomon's palace complex where he was to judge.

HallOfPillars.desc: A building in Solomon's palace complex.

HallOfTheThrone.desc: A building in Solomon's palace complex.

Ham.desc: Ham of Zuzim: A location inhabited by the Zuzim, which was subdued by Chedorlaomer and the allied kings.

Ham.2.desc: Ham Egypt: A nation; another name for Egypt.

Hamath.desc: A town on the Orontes River in Syria; capital of Aramean kingdom; its inhabitants were relocated to Samaria by the king of Assyria.

Hammath.desc: Hammath of Naphtali: A fortified town in the territory of Naphtali.

Hammon.desc: Hammon of Asher: A town in the territory of Asher.

Hammon.2.desc: Hammon of Naphtali: A Levitical town in the territory of Naphtali.

Hammoth-dor.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Naphtali, assigned to the clan of Gershon.

Hamon-gogValley.desc: A valley where the armies of Gog will be buried, according to a prophecy of Ezekiel (Ezekiel 39:11).

Hamonah.desc: A town in the valley where the army of Gog is defeated.

Hanes.desc: A town in Egypt located on an island in the Nile, south of Memphis.

Hannathon.desc: A town in the territory of Zebulun.

Hapharaim.desc: A town in the territory of Issachar.

Hara.desc: A town or region in Assyria along the Habor River; one of the places where the exiles from Samaria were relocated.

Haradah.desc: A location in the Sinai Peninsula, between Mount Shepher and Makheloth, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan.

Haran.desc: A town in northern Mesopotamia where Abraham's father settled when coming from Ur, and where his relatives continued to live. It was later destroyed by Assyria and was a trading partner of Tyre.

Harmon.desc: An unknown region, where the inhabitants of Bashan were to be exiled.

Harod.desc: Home of two of David's fighting men, Shammah and Elika.

Harod.1.desc: The location where Gideon encamped with his army before attacking the MIdianites.

Harosheth-hagoyim.desc: A town north of Israel; residence of Sisera, army commander of Jabin, king of Hazor (Judges 4:2).

Hashmonah.desc: A location in the Sinai Peninsula, between Mithkah and Moseroth, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan.

Hauran.desc: A region northeast of Israel mentioned in Ezekiel's description of Israel's borders.

Havilah.desc: A region, possibly located in Arabia, surrounded by the Pishon River; known for fragrant resins and precious stones (ABD).

Havvoth-jair.desc: Settlements in Gilead that were taken by Jair, of the tribe of Manasseh (Numbers 32:41); in certain passages associated with a person of the same name.

Hazar-addar.desc: A town in the territory of Judah.

Hazar-enan.desc: A location northeast of Israel; also known as Hazar-Enon.

Hazar-gaddah.desc: A town in the southern territory of Judah, near the border of Edom.

Hazar-shual.desc: A location in the territory of Judah, assigned to the tribe of Simeon.

Hazar-susah.desc: A location in the territory of Simeon; also known as Hazar-Susah.

Hazazon-tamar.desc: An oasis in the wilderness of the territory of Judah, on the western shore of the Dead Sea; also known as En-Gedi.

Hazer-hatticon.desc: A location on the border of Hauran, mentioned in Ezekiel's description of Israel's borders.

Hazeroth.desc: A location in the Sinai Peninsula, between Kibroth-Hattaavah and Rithmah, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan; not far from the place where Moses repeated the law.

Hazor.desc: Hazor of Galilee: A fortified town in Galilee.

Hazor-hadattah.desc: A village in the south of the territory of Judah, near Edom.

Hazor.2.desc: Hazor of Judah: A town in the territory of Judah.

Hazor.4.desc: Hazor of Benjamin: A town or village in the territory of Benjamin, after the exile.

Hazor.5.desc: Hazor of Jeremiah: A kingdom destroyed by Nebuchadnezzar.

Hebron.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Judah, assigned to the clan of Aaron; formerly known as Kiriath-Arba. The patriarchs were buried in a cave there.

Helam.desc: A location near the Jordan River where David defeated the Arameans.

Helbah.desc: A town in the territory of Asher.

Helbon.desc: A town in Syria that traded wine with Damascus.

Helech.desc: A region, possibly to be identified with Hilakku, in Cilicia; mercenaries from this area were fighting as part of the army of Tyre (Ezekiel 27:11)

Heleph.desc: A border town in the territory of Naphtali.

Helkath.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Asher, assigned to the clan of Gershon.

Helkath-hazzurim.desc: A field near Gibeon where the young men from the armies of Joab and Abner battled.

Hena.desc: A town or area possibly located in upper Mesopotamia (ABD); conquered by the king of Assyria.

Hepher.desc: A town in the territory of West Manasseh, conquered by Joshua and the Israelites.

HeracleopolisMagna.desc: Capital of the 20th nome of ancient Upper Egypt.

Heres.desc: The location east of the Jordan River from which Gideon returned after defeating the Midianites.

Heres.2.desc: A mountain range located east of southeast of Aijalon, in the territory of Dan.

HeresMount.desc: A mountain range located east of south-east of Aijalon; territory of Dan.

Hereth.desc: A forest in the territory of Judah, where David went while fleeing from Saul.

HermonMount.desc: A mountain in the Anti-Lebanon range, northeast of Israel; also known as Senir, Sion, and Sirion.

Heshbon.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Gad, assigned to the clan of Merari; former residence of Sihon, king of the Amorites (who had captured it from Moab); later occupied by Moab.

Heshmon.desc: A town in the southern territory of Judah, near the border of Edom.

Hethlon.desc: A town or village at the northern boundary of Israel.

Hezron.desc: A town in the territory of Judah.

Hierapolis.desc: A city in Phrygia near Colossae and Laodicea.

labels: Valley of the Son of Hinnom
valley of the children of Hinnom
HinnomValley.desc: A valley west and south of Jerusalem; known for the idol worship that took place there.

Hippo.desc: A Roman city, home to Saint Augustine, on the northern coast of Africa where several early church councils were held; modern-day Annaba, Algeria.

Hippos.desc: A Decapolis city in the Golan Heights, east of the Sea of Galilee.

Hobah.desc: A town north of Damascus to where Abraham routed Chedorlaomer's army.

Holon.desc: Holon of Judah: A Levitical town in the territory of Judah; assigned to the clan of Aaron.

Holon.2.desc: Holon of Moab: A town in Moab.

HolyPlace.desc: Holy Place of the Tabernacle: The outer sanctuary of the tabernacle, described in terms of its holiness.

HolyPlace.2.desc: Holy Place of the Temple: The outer sanctuary of the temple, described in terms of its holiness.

Hor-haggidgad.desc: A location in the Sinai Peninsula, between Bene-Jaakan and Yotbathah, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan; probably to be identified with Gudgodah.

HorMount.desc: Mount Hor of Edom: A mountain on the Edomite border where Aaron died (Numbers 33:38–39).

HorMount.2.desc: Mount Hor Northern: A mountain marking the northern border of Israel (Numbers 34:7–8); possibly Mount Hermon.

HorebMount.desc: A mountain located on the Sinai Peninsula; another name for Mount Sinai.

Horem.desc: A fortified town in the territory of Naphtali.

Horesh.desc: A location on the hill of Hachilah in the wilderness of Ziph, in the territory of Judah; one of the places where David hid from Saul.

Hormah.desc: A town where the Amalekites and the Canaanites defeated the Israelites; later conquered by the Israelites and allotted to the tribe of Simeon.

Horonaim.desc: Horonaim of Moab: A town in Moab mentioned in prophetic oracles against Moab (Isa 15:5; Jer 48:3–5; Jer 48:34).

Horonaim.2.desc: Horonaim 2 Samuel 13:34: A location mentioned in the 2 Samuel 13:34 (Greek version) in connection to Absalom's men killing Amnon.

HorseGate.desc: A gate in Jerusalem, near the palace, where Queen Athaliah was killed (2 Chronicles23:15).

Hosah.desc: A town in the territory of Asher.

House of the Forest of the Lebanon
The Palace of the Lebanon Forest
Palace of the Forest of Lebanon
house of the timber from Lebanon
house of the timber of Lebanon
HouseOfTheForestOfLebanon.desc: A very large building in Jerusalem built by King Solomon, which consisted of four rows of pillars of cedar wood; this cedar wood likely came from the forests of Lebanon, located north of Israel; literally "House of the Forest of Lebanon."
