House of the Forest of Lebanon

Hukkok.desc: A town in the territory of Naphtali.

Hukok.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Asher.

Humtah.desc: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah.

Ibleam.desc: A town in the territory of Manasseh, also known as Bileam; one of the Levitical cities of refuge assigned to the clan of Kohath (Numbers 14:45).

Iconium.desc: A city in Lycaonia, in southern Asia Minor; Paul and Barnabas traveled here during Paul's first missionary journey.

Idalah.desc: A town in the territory of Zebulun, perhaps about 15 kilometers north of Megiddo.

Idumea.desc: A mountainous region south of Judea and north of the earlier region known as Edom.

Iim.desc: A town in the southern territory of Judah, near the border of Edom.

Ijon.desc: A town in the territory of Naphtali, part of the northern kingdom of Israel; conquered by Ben-Hadad of Syria during the reign of King Baasha, and by Tiglath-Pileser of Assyria during the reign of Pekah.

India.desc: A land located east of Persia, which formed the eastern boundary of the kingdom ruled by Ahasuerus (Esther 1:1).

InspectionGate.desc: A gate in Jerusalem opposite the house of the temple servants and the merchants (Nehemiah 3:31).

Iphtah.desc: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

IphtahelValley.desc: A valley located on the boundary between the territories of Zebulun and Asher.

Ir-moab.desc: A city on the Arnon River where Balaam met with Balak.

Ir-shemesh.desc: A town in the territory of Dan.

Irpeel.desc: A town in the territory of Benjamin.

Israel.desc: The land inhabited by the Israelites.

Italy.desc: A peninsula in Southern Europe, surrounded by the Adriatic, Ionian, and Tyrrhenian seas.

Ithlah.desc: A town in the territory of Dan.

Ithnan.desc: A town in the southern territory of Judah, near the border of Edom.

Ituraea.desc: A small province northeast of the Sea of Galilee, which was part of the tetrarchy of Philip (Luke 3:1).

Ivvah.desc: A town, also known as Avvah; its inhabitants were relocated to Samaria by the king of Samaria.

Iye-abarim.desc: A location east of Moab, along the route of the exodus; also known as Iim.

Jaar.desc: A location mentioned in Psalm 136:2; possibly a reference to Kiriath-Jearim.

Jabbok.desc: A river flowing west from its source near Rabbath-Ammon to empty into the Jordan River about 40 km north of the Dead Sea.

Jabesh-gilead.desc: A town in Gilead in Transjordan.

Jabez.desc: A town in the territory of Judah.

Jabneel.desc: Jabneel of Judah: A town in the northwestern edge of the territory of Judah, on the coastal plain; possibly to be identified with Jabneh,

Jabneel.2.desc: Jabneel of Naphtali: A town in the territory of Naphtali.

JacobsWell.desc: A well east of Shechem, associated with the patriarch Jacob, where Jesus spoke with the Samaritan woman (John 4:6).

Jagur.desc: A town on Judah's southeastern border, near Edom.

Jahaz.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Reuben, assigned to the clan of Merari; later occupied by Moab.

Janim.desc: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah.

Janoah.desc: Janoah of Galilee: A town in the north of Israel, in Galilee, conquered by Tiglath-Pileser, king of Assyria.

Janoah.2.desc: Janoah of Ephraim: A town at the boundary between the territories of Ephraim and Manasseh.

Japhia.desc: A town in the territory of Zebulun.

Jarmuth.desc: Jarmuth of Judah: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Jarmuth.2.desc: Jarmuth of Issachar: A Levitical town in the territory of Issachar, assigned to the clan of Gershon.

Jattir.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Judah; assigned to the clan of Aaron.

Javan.desc: A nation usually identified with Greece; considered descendants of Japheth through his son Javan.

Jazer.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Gad, in Gilead, assigned to the clan of Merari; former Amorite territory; later occupied by Moab.

JearimMount.desc: A mountain between Kiriath-Jearim and Beth-Shemesh, in the territory of Judah.

Jebus.desc: A town of the Jebusites that later became Jerusalem.

Jegar-sahadutha.desc: A pile of stones east of the Jordan, possibly in Gilead, erected by Jacob and Laban to commemorate their agreement.

Jehud.desc: A coastal town in the territory of Dan.

Jericho.desc: Jericho Old Testament: A town northwest of the Dead Sea in the territory of Benjamin; first town conquered by Israel after they entered Canaan.

Jericho.2.desc: Jericho New Testament: A city in Judea, not far from the north end of the Dead Sea; rebuilt by Herod south of Old Testament Jericho.

JerichoValley.desc: A valley near Jericho, north of the Dead Sea.

Jeruel.desc: A part of the wilderness in the territory of Judah, near the Ascent of Ziz, where the Israelites were victorious over a coalition of invading Moabites, Ammonites, Edomites, and Meunites (2 Chronicles20:16).

Jerusalem.desc: The capital city of Israel in the territory of Judah, formerly referred to as Salem and Jebus. It was conquered by King David, who made it the capital of his kingdom (2 Samuel 5:6–9).

Jeshanah.desc: A town in the territory of Ephraim.

Jeshimon.desc: A desert area visible from Mount Pisgah.

Jeshua.desc: A town in the territory of Judah.

Jetur.desc: A small province, also known as Ituraea, located to the northeast of the Sea of Galilee.

Jezreel.desc: Jezreel of Judah: A town in the hill county of the territory of Judah.

Jezreel.2.desc: Jezreel of Issachar: A town in the territory of Issachar.

Jogbehah.desc: A town on the border between the territories of Gad and Reuben, near Ammonite territory.

Jokdeam.desc: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Jokmeam.desc: Jokmeam of Ephraim: A Levitical town in the territory of Ephraim.

Jokneam.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Zebulun, near Mount Carmel; assigned to the clan of Merari.

Joktheel.desc: Joktheel of Judah: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Joktheel.2.desc: Sela of Edom: A town in Edom where Amaziah defeated the Edomites; renamed Joktheel.

Joppa.desc: A seaport town in the territory of Dan.

Jordan.desc: A river flowing south from Mount Hermon through the Sea of Galilee into the Dead Sea. Jesus was baptized by John in the Jordan River (Matthew 3:13–17; Mark 1:9–11; Luke 3:21–22; John 1:29–34).

JordanValley.desc: The relatively flat area of land through which the Jordan River flows, from the Sea of Galilee to the Dead Sea; part of the larger Jordan Rift Valley, also known as the Great Rift Valley.

Jotapata.desc: A village northwest of Cana, in the region of Galilee; possibly biblical Jotbah. It was sieged by Rome during the First Jewish Revolt.

Jotbah.desc: A town in the territory of Naphtali.

Jotbathah.desc: A location in the Sinai Peninsula, between Hor-Haggidgad and Abronah, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan.

Judea.desc: A region in southern Palestine associated with the tribe of Judah.

Judea.2.desc: Judah Persian Period: The territory of the tribe of Judah during the Persian period.

Juttah.desc: A Levitical town in the hill country of the territory of Judah; assigned to the clan of Aaron.

Kabzeel.desc: A town in the territory of Judah; also known as Jekabzeel.

Kadesh.desc: A location between Gilead and Dan-Jaan visited by David's military commanders during the census.

Kadesh-barnea.desc: A town in the wilderness of Zin, in the northern part of the Sinai Peninsula, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan; it is also the location of the Meribah Spring. Spies were sent out into Canaan from this place; it later marked the southern border of the territory of Judah.

Kain.desc: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah.

Kamon.desc: A town in Gilead; burial place of Jair the judge.

Kanah.desc: Kanah of Asher: A town in the territory of Asher; probably modern Qana, which is 10 kilometers southeast of Tyre.

Kanah.2.desc: Kanah Brook: A brook or wadi marking the boundary of the territory of Ephraim, separating it from Manasseh, 8 km southwest of Shechem.

Karkor.desc: A location east of the Jordan River, where Gideon attacked the Midianite kings Zebah and Zalmunnah.

Karnaim.desc: A town in Bashan; possibly to be identified with Beeshterah, Ashtaroth, and Ashteroth-Karnaim.

Kartah.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Zebulun; assigned to the clan of Merari.

Kartan.desc: A Levitical town of refuge in the territory of Naphtali, assigned to the clan of Gershon; probably to be identified with Kartan.

Kattath.desc: A town in the territory of Zebulun.

Kedemoth.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Reuben, east of the Dead Sea and north of the Arnon; former territory of the Amorites; assigned to the clan of Merari.

Kedesh.desc: Kedesh in Upper Galilee: A town in Upper Galilee, in the territory of Naphtali; assigned to the clan of Gershon of tribe of Levi as a town of refuge (Joshua 21:31); later captured by Tiglath-Pileser.

labels: Kedesh in the land of Naphtali
Kedesh-naphtali.desc: A location in the territory of Naphtali from where Deborah summoned Barak to march against Sisera; possibly to be identified with Kedesh (in Upper Galilee) or Kedesh (of Issachar).

Kedesh.2.desc: Kedesh of Judah: A town in the southern territory of Judah, near the border of Edom; also known as En Mishpat, Kadesh, and Kadesh-Barnea.

Kedesh.3.desc: Kedesh of Issachar: A Levitical town in the territory of Issachar, assigned to the clan of Gershon; possibly to be identified with Kishion.

Kehelathah.desc: A location in the Sinai Peninsula, between Rissah and Mount Shepher, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan.

Keilah.desc: A fortified town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Kenath.desc: A town located east of the Sea of Galilee.

Kerioth-hezron.desc: A town between Hebron and Arad in the territory of Judah; also known as Hazor.

KhirbetEd-Deir.desc: A village southwest of Bethlehem; possibly Eltekon.

Kibroth-hattaavah.desc: A location in the Sinai Peninsula, between the wilderness of Sinai and Hazeroth, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan; people were buried there following a plague that came as a punishment from God.

Kibzaim.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Ephraim, assigned to the clan of Kohath.

Kidron.desc: A valley located east of Jerusalem between the ancient city and the Mount of Olives.

Kinah.desc: A town on the southern border of the territory of Judah; possibly related to the Kenites.

KingsHighway.desc: A road leading through the Transjordan along the desert border, connecting Damascus with the Gulf of Aqabah.

KingsValley.desc: A valley near Salem where Abraham met Melchizedek (Genesis 14:17); also known as the valley of Shaveh.

Kir.desc: Kir Region: A region of Assyria to which Syrians were taken as captives.

Kir-hareseth.desc: A town in Moab; also known as Kir-Heres.

Kir.2.desc: Kir of Moab: A town in Moab; probably to be identified with Kir-Hareseth.

Kiriath-huzoth.desc: A town in Moab where Balak made a sacrifice while traveling with Balaam (Numbers 22:39–40).

Kiriath-jearim.desc: A town located in the hill country of the territory of Judah; one of the four Hivite cities that made a covenant with Joshua (Joshua 9:17–18); also known as Kiriath-Baal, Baalah, and Baale-Judah, .

Kiriathaim.desc: Kiriathaim of Reuben: A town in the territory of Reuben; later part of Moab.

Kiriathaim.2.desc: A Levitical town of refuge in the territory of Naphtali, assigned to the clan of Gershon; probably to be identified with Kartan.

Kishion.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Issachar, assigned to the clan of Gershon; possibly to be identified with Kedesh.

Kishon.desc: A river that drains the western portion of the Plain of Esdraelon from Megiddo to the Mediterranean, fed by springs from Gilboa and the foot of the Carmel range; location where Sisera was defeated and where Elijah killed the prophets of Baal.

Kitron.desc: A town in the territory of Zebulun inhabited by Canaanites.

Kittim.desc: An island in the Mediterranean Sea; possibly to be identified with Cyprus.

Koa.desc: A nation in Mesopotamia, east of the Tigris.

Kue.desc: A kingdom located in southeastern Turkey, known as Cilicia in Greco-Roman period; famous for its horses.

Laban.desc: A location in the Sinai Peninsula, between Rimmon-Perez and Rissah, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan, not far from the place where Moses repeated the law; possibly to be identified with Libnah.

Lachish.desc: A fortified town in the foothills of the territory of Judah, where Amaziah, king of Judah, was assassinated.

Lahmam.desc: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Laishah.desc: A location in the territory of Benjamin.

Lakkum.desc: A town in the territory of Naphtali.

Laodicea.desc: A city in Phrygia in Asia Minor near Colossae and Hierapolis; one of the seven cities addressed in Revelation.

Lasea.desc: A city on the south coast of the island of Crete near Fair Havens.

Lasha.desc: A town in the southern boundary of Canaanite territory.

Lasharon.desc: A town in Canaan which was taken by Joshua (Joshua 12:18); possibly "of Sharon" referring to the Plain of Sharon.

Latopolis.desc: A city in Upper Egypt, on the west bank of the Nile; modern-day Esna.

Leb-kamai.desc: A cryptic name for Chaldea, a region in southern Babylonia.

Lebanon.desc: A region in West Asia, between Syria in the north and Israel in the south.

LebanonMount.desc: A range of mountains north of Israel known for the cedar and other trees growing there.

LebanonValley.desc: A valley between the Lebanon and Anti-Lebanon mountains.

Lebaoth.desc: A town in the territory of Simeon; also referred to as Beth-Leboath.

Lebo-hamath.desc: A town located south of Hamath on the northern border of Canaan.

Lehem.desc: A man from the tribe of Judah; possible place name mentioned in 1 Chronicles4:22.

Lehi.desc: A location near Judah's border with Philistia where Samson killed many Philistines with a donkey jawbone.

LeptisMagna.desc: A city on the northern coast of Africa. It was originally a Phoenician settlement and later became a Roman colony.

Lesbos.desc: An island in the northeastern Aegean Sea.

Libnah.desc: Libnah Campsite: A location in the Sinai Peninsula, between Rimmon-Perez and Rissah, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan; possibly to be identified with Laban.

Libnah.2.desc: Libnah of Judah: A Levitical town in the foothills of the territory of Judah; assigned to the clan of Aaron.

Libya.desc: A country in North Africa; Libyans were among those present at Pentecost (Acts 2:10).

Lo-debar.desc: A town east of the Jordan River, assigned to the tribe of Gad.

Lod.desc: A town in the territory of Benjamin; built by Shemed.

Londinium.desc: The capital city of Roman Britain; modern-day London.

LowerGulloth.desc: A spring given to Achsah by her father Caleb as a wedding gift.

LowerPool.desc: A pool in Jerusalem mentioned in Isa 22:9.

Lud.2.desc: A land and ethnic group located in northern Africa; regarded as descendants of Mizraim son of Ham; often fighting in the Egyptian army.

Lugdunum.desc: A Roman city in southeast France; modern-day Lyon. Christians were persecuted here in 177.

Luhith.desc: A town located in Moab at a relatively high elevation.

Lutetia.desc: A Roman city in northern France; modern-day Paris. Beginning in the third century AD, it was a center of early Christianity.

Luxeuil.desc: A Roman town in eastern France, which later became an important center for Christian monasticism. Luxeuil Abbey was founded here by Saint Columbanus at the end of the sixth century.

Luz.desc: Luz of Israel: A town, later known as Bethel, on the boundary of the territories of Ephraim and Benjamin.

Luz.2.desc: Luz of the Hittites: A town in the territory of the Hittites founded by a man who helped the Israelites conquer Bethel.

Lycaonia.desc: A province in the interior of Asia Minor; Paul and Barnabas fled to Lystra and Derbe in this region when the people of Iconium sought to stone them.

Lycia.desc: A region on the south coast of Asia Minor.

Lydia.desc: A province in Western Asia Minor.

Lystra.desc: A city in Lycaonia in Asia Minor, northwest of Derbe; Paul met Timothy there.

Maacah.desc: A small Aramean nation located northeast of the Sea of Galilee.

Maarath.desc: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah.

Maareh-geba.desc: A location from which the Israelites led an ambush against Gibeah.

Macedonia.desc: A Roman province in Greece; Paul had a vision of a man of Macedonia who pleaded with him to come and preach the gospel (Acts 16:9–10).

Machaerus.desc: A hilltop fortress east of the Dead Sea, where John the Baptist may have been imprisoned and beheaded.

Machbenah.desc: A town in the territory of Judah.

Machpelah.desc: A location containing a field and a cave, near Hebron, bought from Ephron the Hittite and used as a burial place for Abraham, Sarah, Isaac, Rebekah, Jacob, and Leah.

Madmannah.desc: A town in the territory of Judah.

Madmen.desc: A town in Moab mentioned in Jer 48:2.

Madmenah.desc: A town in the territory of Benjamin.

Madon.desc: A town in Canaan that fought with Jabin, king of Hazor, against the Israelites at the Waters of Merom.

Magadan.desc: An uncertain location west of the Sea of Galilee to which Jesus came after he fed the 4,000 (Matthew 15:39).

Magdala.desc: A town on the western shore of the Sea of Galilee; possible hometown of Mary Magdalene and, according to the KJV, the location where Jesus sailed to after feeding the multitudes.

Magog.desc: A cryptic name to designate an enemy to be conquered by the Messiah.

Mahalab.desc: A border town in the territory of Asher; sometimes not translated as a place.

Mahanaim.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Gad, assigned to the clan of Merari; capital of the kingdom of Isboseth, son of Saul.

Mahaneh-dan.desc: A location between Zorah and Eshtaol were the Danites encamped before traveling to the hill country of Ephraim; literally "camp of Dan.

Makaz.desc: A town in the territory of Judah during time of King Solomon, under the control of Ben-Deker.

Makheloth.desc: A location in the Sinai Peninsula, between Haradah and Tahath, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan.

Makkedah.desc: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Malta.desc: An island south of Sicily where Paul was shipwrecked on his voyage to Rome.

Mamre.desc: A location with oak trees near Hebron, where Abraham pitched his tents.

Manahath.desc: A town in the territory of Judah.

Maon.desc: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah; residence of Nabal and his wife Abigail, who later married David.

Marah.desc: A location in the wilderness of Etham where the Israelites encamped shortly after crossing the Sea of Reeds on their way from Egypt to Canaan; here bitter water was made drinkable.

Mareal.desc: A village in the territory of Zebulun.

Mareshah.desc: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Marmoutier.desc: A town in northeastern France where Marmoutier Abbey is located.

Maroth.desc: A town in the territory of Judah.

Masada.desc: A fortification on a plateau overlooking the western edge of the Dead Sea. It was sieged by the Romans during the First Jewish Revolt.

Masrekah.desc: A town in Edom; residence of Samlah, king of Edom.

Massah.desc: A location, also called Meribah, along the route of the exodus; one of the places where the Israelites rebelled against Moses because of a lack of water.

Massilia.desc: A Greek seaport city on the southeastern coast of France; modern-day Marseille.

Mattanah.desc: A location along the route of the exodus.

Me-jarkon.desc: A stream in the territory of Dan, near Joppa.

Mearah.desc: A location between Tyre and Sidon included in a list of places that the Israelites had yet been unable to conquer.

Meconah.desc: A town in the territory of Judah.

Medeba.desc: A town in the territory of Reuben, in Moab.

Media.desc: A nation and their territory; regarded as founded by Madai; the empire was consolidated in the 6th–5th BCE and stretched from Mesopotamia to Turkey.

Mediolanum.desc: A Roman city in northern Italy and center of early Christianity; modern-day Milan.

Megiddo.desc: A town in the territory of Manasseh, southwest of the Jezreel Valley, where King Josiah of Judah was killed during his battle with Pharaoh Neco; former Canaanite kingdom.

Memphis.desc: A town in Egypt; residence and capital of many of its kings (ABD).

Mephaath.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Reuben, assigned to the clan of Merari; later occupied by Moab.

Merathaim.desc: A region south of Babylon; possibly a symbolic name for Babylon.

Meribah.desc: A location along the route of the exodus, also called Massah; one of the places where the Israelites rebelled against Moses because of a lack of water.

Merom.desc: A spring where the alliance of northern Canaanite kings gathered to fight against Joshua and the Israelites.

Meroz.desc: A town north of Canaan cursed by Deborah because of their unwillingness to help Barak's army in their fight against the army of Sisera.

Mesha.desc: Mesha of Joktan: One of the boundaries of the territory of the descendants of Joktan.

Meshech.desc: A nation named after Meshech, son of Japheth and grandson of Noah.

Mesopotamia.desc: A region between the Tigris and Euphrates Rivers; the Garden of Eden was located here.

Metheg-ammah.desc: A location taken by David from the control of the Philistines.

Michmash.desc: A town in the territory of Benjamin.

Michmethath.desc: A town on the border of the territories of Ephraim and Manasseh.

Middin.desc: A town in the wilderness of the territory of Judah.

MiddleGate.desc: A gate in Jerusalem where the officials of Nebuchadnezzar, king of Babylon, gathered after sieging the city (Jer 39:3).

Midian.desc: Son of Keturah, wife of Abraham; regarded as ancestor of an ethnic group with the same name, and the region they occupied.

Migdal-el.desc: A fortified town in the territory of Naphtali.

Migdal-gad.desc: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Migdol.desc: Migdol Campsite: A location in eastern Egypt, near the Sea of Reeds and close to Pi-Hahiroth, where the Israelites encamped before crossing the Sea of Reeds on their way from Egypt to Canaan.

Migron.desc: A town in the territory of Benjamin.

Miletus.desc: A seaport city of Caria, on the west coast of Asia Minor; Paul met with the Ephesian elders here.

Millo.desc: Exact meaning unsure; probably part of the fortifications of the City of David, often identified with the so-called "stepped stone structure" on the east.

Minni.desc: A nation in Armenia; called in a prophecy to punish Babylon (Jer 51:27).

Minnith.desc: A town in Ammon; captured by Jephthah; possibly known for its wheat.

Mishal.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Asher, assigned to the clan of Gershon; also known as Mashal.

Misrephoth-maim.desc: A location near Sidon where the Israelites stopped pursuing the Canaanite kings that had gathered to fight against them (Joshua 11:8).

Mithkah.desc: A location in the Sinai Peninsula, between Terah and Hashmonah, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan.

Mitylene.desc: The chief city on the island of Lesbos in the Aegean Sea.

MizarMount.desc: Exact meaning unknown; possibly an unknown mountain near Mount Hermon.

Mizpah.desc: Mizpah of Benjamin: A town in the territory of Benjamin where Israel assembled after the atrocity that was committed in Gibeah, and where Israel assembled during the time of Samuel's leadership; residence of the governor Gedaliah after the destruction of Jerusalem.

Mizpah.2.desc: Mizpah of Gilead: A town in Gilead where Jacob and Laban built a monument after their reconciliation; residence of Jephthah.

Mizpeh.desc: Mizpeh of Moab: A location in Moab; residence of Moabite king.

Mizpeh.2.desc: Mizpeh of Benjamin: A town in the territory of Benjamin where Israel assembled after the atrocity that was committed in Gibeah; where Israel assembled during Samuel's leadership; residence of the governor Gedaliah after the destruction of Jerusalem.

Mizpeh.3.desc: Mizpeh of Judah: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

MizpehValley.desc: A location near Mount Hermon inhabited by the Hivites.

Moab.desc: A nation and its territory situated east of the Dead Sea; regarded as founded by a son of Lot.

MoabPlains.desc: The region north of the Dead Sea and east of the Jordan River, where Moses deilvered his final message to the Israelites.

Moladah.desc: A town in the territory of Judah and later assigned to Simeon.

Montecassino.desc: A hilltop in central Italy, southeast of Rome, where the Montecassino Abbey is located. The abbey was founded by Saint Benedict in the sixth century.

Moreh.desc: A location with a sacred tree where Abraham encamped.

Moreh.2.desc: A hill where the Midianites encamped during time of Gideon.

Moresheth-gath.desc: A town in the territory of Judah where the prophet Micah came from.

Moriah.desc: The land where Abraham was to sacrifice his son, Isaac, and where Solomon built the temple.

MoriahMount.desc: A hill in Jerusalem where Solomon built the temple.

Mortar.desc: Literally "mortar"; exact meaning unknown; possibly a relatively low part of Jerusalem used as market area, referred to as such because of its mortar-like shape.

Moseroth.desc: A location in the Sinai Peninsula, between Hashmonah and Bene-Jaakan, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan.

MostHolyPlace.desc: Most Holy Place of the Temple: The innermost room at the back of the main temple building; location of the ark of the covenant; regarded as the holiest place.

MostHolyPlace.1.desc: Most Holy Place of the Tabernacle: The innermost room at the back of the tabernacle; location of the ark of the covenant; regarded as the holiest place.

MountAthos.desc: A mountain on a peninsula in northern Greece; an important location for Christian monasticism.

MountColzim.desc: A mountain in Egypt, west of the Gulf of Suez, associated with Saint Anthony the Great.

MountZemaraim.desc: A mountain in the Ephraimite hill country, in the northern kingdom of Israel, where Abijah, king of Judah, addressed Jeroboam, king of Israel, before battle (2 Chronicles13:4).

Mozah.desc: A town in the territory of Benjamin.

Myra.desc: A city on the south coast of Lycia in Asia Minor where Paul boarded an Alexandrian ship on his way to Rome.

Mysia.desc: A province in northwest Asia Minor where Paul passed through during his second missionary journey.

Naamah.desc: Naamah of Judah: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Naamah.2.desc: Naamah of Zophar: A location possibly in Arabia; home of Job's friend Zophar.

Naarah.desc: A location in the Jordan Valley, in the territory of Ephraim.

Naaran.desc: A location in the Jordan Valley, in the territory of Ephraim; also known as Naarah.

Nahalal.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Zebulun, assigned to the clan of Merari; also known as Nahalol.

Nahaliel.desc: A location along the route of the exodus, between Mattanah and Bamoth, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan.

Nahor.desc: A city in northwestern Mesopotamia; hometown of Nahor, Abraham's brother, and where Abraham's servant found Rebekah, the wife of Isaac.

Nain.desc: A city in southern Galilee where Jesus raised a widow's son.

Naioth.desc: A location near Ramah where David and Samuel went when the former had to flee from Saul.

Naphoth-dor.desc: A town in the territory of Manasseh.

labels: Monastery of the Archangel Gabriel at Naqlun
Naqlun.desc: The location of a Coptic monastery in the Faiyum Oasis in northern Egypt.

Narbo.desc: A Roman city in southern Gaul; modern-day Narbonne, France.

Nazareth.desc: A town in south central Galilee, where Jesus lived as a child (Matthew 2:23).

Nazianzus.desc: A town in the region of Cappadocia in Asia Minor, associated with one of the Cappadocian Fathers, Saint Gregory of Naziansus.

Neah.desc: A town in the territory of Zebulun.

Neapolis.desc: The harbor of Philippi in Macedonia; Paul and his companions sailed here from Samothrace.

Neapolis.2.desc: Neapolis Nablus: A town located between Mount Gerizim and Mount Ebal; modern-day Nablus.

Neballat.desc: A town or village in the territory of Benjamin after the exile.

Nebo.desc: Nebo of Moab: A town in the territory of Reuben; later part of Moab.

Nebo.2.desc: Nebo of Judah: A town in the territory of Judah.

Nebo.3.desc: Nebo Ezra 10:43: Possibly a location associated with a person of the same name; an ancestor of 52 exiles who returned to Judah with Zerubbabel.

NeboMount.desc: A mountain in Moab, near Jericho, where Moses had a view of the promised land before he died (Deuteronomy 34:1–4).

Negeb.desc: A area of land located in the south of Israel, consisting of little vegetation and with very little annual rainfall; inhabited by numerous peoples, initially by the Canaanites in Arad and the Amalekites, and later, the people of Judah.

Nehelam.desc: Exact meaning unsure; possibly an inhabitant of an unknown town called Nehelam.

Neiel.desc: A town in the territory of Asher.

Nephtoah.desc: A spring on the boundary between the territories of Judah and Benjamin.

Netaim.desc: A town in the territory of Judah; residence of potters.

Netophah.desc: A town in the territory of Judah.

NewGate.desc: A gate of the temple in Jerusalem in the days of Jeremiah.

Nezib.desc: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Nibshan.desc: A town located in the wilderness of the territory of Judah.

Nicaea.desc: A Greek city in northwestern Anatolia, where the First and Second Councils of Nicaea were held.

Nicomedia.desc: A city in the province of Bithynia; modern-day Izmit, Turkey.

Nicopolis.desc: A seaport city on the west coast of Greece, which Paul visited during his travels (Tit 3:12).

Nile.desc: A large body of flowing water located in Egypt; very important to transportation, irrigation, and life in Egypt.

Nimrah.desc: A town in the territory of Gad; also known as Beth-Nimrah.

Nimrim.desc: A body of water located in Moab denounced by the prophets Jeremiah and Isaiah.

Nimrod.desc: Nimrod Nation: A kingdom in Mesopotamia; most likely another name for Assyria.

Nineveh.desc: A town in northern Mesopotamia near Mosul, on the east bank of the Tigris River; built by Nimrod after the flood. It was the capital of Assyria; the prophet Jonah preached against the town.

Nob.desc: A town in the territory of Benjamin; important religious center where many priests lived.

Nobah.desc: Nobah of Manasseh: A town located east of the Jordan River and at some time part of territory of Manasseh; also known as Kenath.

Nobah.2.desc: Nobah Judges 8:11: A town near Jogbehah and the caravan route Gideon used to pursue the Midianites.

Nod.desc: The location where Cain fled after he was cursed for killing his brother Abel.

Nohah.desc: A location west of Gibeah in the territory of Benjamin; possibly not a place name.

Nola.desc: A city in southern Italy where Caesar Augustus died.

Nyssa.desc: A town in the region of Cappadocia in Asia Minor, associated with one of the Cappadocian Fathers, Saint Gregory of Nyssa.

Oboth.desc: A location in Edom along the route of the exodus where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan.

OldPool.desc: A pool in Jerusalem mentioned in Isa 22:11.

labels: Ascent of the Mount of Olives
OlivesMount.desc: A mountain, named for its olive groves, east of Jerusalem and the Kidron Valley and near Gethsemane; an important location during the final week of Jesus' life. The southern peak, where Solomon built shrines to Chemosh and Molech (1Ki 11:7), is often referred to as the "Mount of Offense."

On.desc: A town in Lower-Egypt, to be identified with Heliopolis; center of worship of solar deities such as Re and Atum (ABD).

Ono.desc: A town in the territory of Benjamin built by Shemed.

Ophel.desc: A fortified hill somewhere on the easter ridge of Jerusalem, north of the City of David and south of Solomon's temple.

Ophir.desc: A region probably in southern Arabia; known for its gold.

Ophni.desc: A town in the territory of Benjamin.

Ophrah.desc: Ophrah of Benjamin: A town in the territory of Benjamin.

Ophrah.2.desc: Ophrah of Manasseh: A town in the territory of Manasseh.

Paddan-aram.desc: A region in upper Mesopotamia, located around the great bend of the Euphrates River in northern Syria; ancestral home of Abraham’s family (ABD); also known as Aram-Naharaim.

Pamphylia.desc: A province in the southern part of Asia Minor; Paul and his companions traveled here during his first missionary journey.

Paphos.desc: A seaport city on the southwest coast of the island of Cyprus, where Paul and Barnabas encountered Elymas the sorcerer (Acts 13:6–12).

Parah.desc: A town in the territory of Benjamin.

Paran.desc: A mountain in the wilderness of Paran.

Parbar.desc: An area enclosed by walls or buildings; part of the temple complex.

Parvaim.desc: An unknown location from where Solomon obtained gold; possibly in Arabia.

Patara.desc: A city in Lycia on the southwest coast of Asia Minor where Paul's ship made a stop on his journey to Jerusalem.

Pathros.desc: A region in the upper Nile area of southern Egypt.

Patmos.desc: A small, rock island in the Aegean Sea where John received his revelation.

Patras.desc: A seaport city in western Greece.

Pau.desc: A town in Edom where King Hadad lived; also called Pai.

Pekod.desc: An ethnic group and their territory, located east of the Tigris River.

Pella.desc: A city south of the Sea of Galilee and east of the Jordan River.

Pelusium.desc: A town located at the north-eastern border of Egypt (ABD).

Penuel.desc: A town on the Jabbok River; also known as Peniel.

labels: Gate of the Children of the People
PeoplesGate.desc: A gate in the walls of Jerusalem.

Peor.desc: The location of the temple of Baal-Peor.

PerazimMount.desc: A mountain where king David defeated the Philistines (2 Samuel 5:20); also known as Baal-Perazim.

Perez-uzza.desc: A location near the threshing floor of Nacon, where Yahweh killed Uzzah because he touched the ark of the covenant.

Perga.desc: A city in Pamphylia, near the south coast of Asia Minor; Paul traveled here during his first missionary journey.

Pergamum.desc: An important city in northwest Asia Minor; one of the seven cities addressed in Revelation.

Persia.desc: A nation and its territory, which was greatly expanded during the reign of Cyrus I.

Pethor.desc: A town north of Mesopotamia; home of Balaam.

Pharpar.desc: A river in Syria, near Damascus.

Philadelphia.desc: A city in the west central part of Asia Minor; one of the seven cities addressed in Revelation.

Philippi.desc: A city in Macedonia; the letter to the Philippians was addressed to the church there.

Philistine.desc: The land of the Philistines, situated along the coast of the Mediterranean and concentrated around the cities of Gaza, Gath, Ekron, Ashdod, and Ashkelon.

Phoenicia.desc: A region along the coast of the Mediterranean Sea to the west and north of Palestine, and its inhabitants.

Phoenix.desc: A seaport on the south coast of Crete where Paul and his shipmates hoped to harbor for the winter before continuing on to Rome.

Phrygia.desc: A district in central Asia Minor through which Paul traveled during his missionary journeys.

Pi-beseth.desc: A town in Egypt, better known as Bubastis.

Pi-hahiroth.desc: A location in eastern Egypt, east of Baal-Zephon and close to Migdol, where the Israelites encamped after turning back from Etham on their way from Egypt to Canaan and crossed the Sea of Reeds.

Pirathon.desc: A town in the hill country of Ephraim.

Pisgah.desc: A mountain in the Abarim range, located in Moab northeast of the Dead Sea, where God showed Moses the promised land (Deuteronomy 34:1–3).

Pishon.1.desc: A river running through the land of Havila; one of the four rivers flowing from the Garden of Eden.

Pisidia.desc: A region in the province of Galatia, in southern Asia Minor.

Pithom.desc: A town in Egypt; one of the two cities for storage that had to be built by the Hebrew slaves.

Poitiers.desc: A city in west-central France, associated with Saint Hilary of Poitiers, who was bishop there in the fourth century.

Pontus.desc: A region in northeast Asia Minor; home of Aquila (Acts 18:2).

PotsherdGate.desc: A gate in the wall of Jerusalem near the valley of Hinnom; possibly another name for the Dung Gate.

Ptolemais.desc: A seaport on the coast of Palestine; Acco in the Old Testament.

Pul.desc: A land and ethnic group located in Asia Minor, possibly to be identified with the Lydians; regarded as descendants of Shem; known as archers.

Punon.desc: A location along the route of the exodus where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan.

Put.desc: A nation descended from a man of the same name; possibly to be identified with Libya.

Puteoli.desc: A city on the coast of Italy, south of Rome; visited by Paul on his journey to Rome.

Qumran.desc: A settlement near the northwestern shore of the Dead Sea, south of Jericho. The Dead Sea Scrolls were discovered nearby within the Qumran Caves.

Raamah.desc: A location in Arabia; named after Raamah, son of Cush.

Rabbah.desc: Rabbah of the Ammonites: A town in Ammon and capital of the Ammonite kingdom; first conquered by Israel on their way from Egypt, and later again by David.

Rabbah.2.desc: Rabbah of Judah: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah.

Rabbith.desc: A town in the territory of Issachar.

Racal.desc: A town in the territory of Judah where David sent some plunder.

Rakkath.desc: A fortified town in the territory of Naphtali.

Rakkon.desc: A location in the territory of Dan.

Ramah.desc: Ramah of Ephraim: A town in the territory of Ephraim, where Samuel lived; also known as Ramathaim Zophim.

Ramah.2.desc: Ramah of the Negev: A town in the territory of Simeon; also known as Ramoth-Negev.

Ramah.3.desc: Ramah of Naphtali: A fortified town in the territory of Naphtali.

Ramah.4.desc: Ramah of Benjamin: A town in the territory of Benjamin, northwest of Jerusalem, where the prophetess Deborah would judge Israel (Judges 4:5).

Ramah.5.desc: Ramah of Gilead: A town in Gilead.

Ramah.6.desc: Ramah of Asher: A town in the territory of Asher.

Ramah.7.desc: Ramah Postexilic: A town in the territory of Benjamin, after the exile.

Ramah.8.desc: Ramah Hill: A hill near Gibeah of Benjamin.

Ramath-lehi.desc: A hill where Samson killed many Philistines with a jawbone.

Ramath-mizpeh.desc: A location in the territory of Gad.

Ramathaim-zophim.desc: A town in the territory of Ephraim; also known as Ramah.

Rameses.desc: A region and town located in the northeastern part of the Nile Delta in Egypt, where Joseph settled his father and brothers and where the Israelite slaves were forced to build a city with the same name; starting point of exodus (ABD).

Ramoth.desc: Ramoth of the Negeb: A town in the territory of Simeon; also known as Ramath Negeb.

Ramoth-gilead.desc: A Levitical town in Gilead, in the territory of Gad; assigned to the clan of Merari.

Raphia.desc: A city southwest of Gaza, near the Egyptian border. It was the location of a battle between Ptolemy IV and ANtiochus III (3 Maccabees 1:1).

Ravenna.desc: A seaport city on the eastern coast of Italy.

Recah.desc: A town in the territory of Judah mentioned in 1 Chronicles4:11–12.

RedSea.desc: A body of salt water located between Egypt and the Sinai Peninsula, which the Israelites crossed after they left Egypt.

RedSea.2.desc: The northeastern arm of the Red Sea.

RedSea.3.desc: The northwestern arm of the Red Sea.

Rehob.desc: Rehob in the North: A town on the border between Dan and Syria; also known as Beth-Rehob.

Rehob.2.desc: Rehob of Asher: A Levitical town in the territory of Asher; assigned to the clan of Gershon.

Rehoboth.desc: Rehoboth Well: A well, dug by herdsmen of Isaac, which, unlike the wells of Esek and Sitnah, did not become a source of contention between them and the herdsmen of Gerar.

Rehoboth-ir.desc: A city in Assyria built by Nimrod after the flood.

Rehoboth.2.desc: Rehoboth on the Euphrates: A town located on the Euphrates River in Mesopotamia; town of King Shual of Edom.

Rekem.desc: A town in the territory of Benjamin.

Remeth.desc: Ramoth of Issachar: A town in the territory of Issachar; also known as Remeth.

Remeth.1.desc: A town in the territory of Issachar.

RephaimValley.desc: A valley on the boundary of the territory of Judah and the territory of Benjamin.

Rephidim.desc: A location in the Sinai Peninsula, between Alush and the wilderness of Sinai, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan.

Resen.desc: A town in Mesopotamia built by Nimrod after the flood, between Nineveh and Calah.

Rezeph.desc: A town conquered by the king of Assyria.

Rhegium.desc: A city on a promontory in the south of Italy; visited by Paul on his journey to Rome.

Rhodes.desc: An island, with a city of the same name, off the southwest coast of Asia Minor; Paul's ship stopped here on his journey to Jerusalem.

Riblah.2.desc: A town on the Orontes River in Syria; also known as Diblah.

Rimmon.desc: Rimmon of Simeon: A town in the territory of Simeon.

Rimmon-perez.desc: A location in the Sinai Peninsula, between Ritmah and Libnah, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan.

Rimmon.2.desc: Rimmon of Zebulun: A Levitical town in the territory of Zebulun; also known as Rimmono.

Rimmon.3.desc: A rock in the territory of Benjamin.

Rimmono.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Zebulun; also known as Rimmon.

Rissah.desc: A location in the Sinai Peninsula, between Libnah and Kehelathah, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan.

Rithmah.desc: A location in the SInai Peninsula, between Kibroth-Hattaavah and Rimmon-Perez, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan.

River.desc: The region of the Euphrates River.

RockOfEscape.desc: A location where David hid in the wilderness of Maon when fleeing from Saul.

Rome.desc: The capital city of the Roman Empire and an early center of Christianity. The letter to the Romans was addressed to the church there.

Sahar.desc: Possibly the name of a location that traded wool with Damascus.

Salamis.desc: A city on the southeast coast of Cyprus; Paul and Barnabas preached here during their first missionary journey.

Salem.desc: A town ruled by Melchizedek during the time of Abraham; to be identified with Jerusalem.

Salim.desc: A place of uncertain location in Samaria, near Aenon where John was baptizing.

Salmone.desc: A promontory on the northeast corner of Crete; Paul's ship sailed near here during his journey to Rome.

SaltSea.desc: A large body of salt water (literally "the sea of salt") located in the basin of the Jordan Valley, east of Judah; the Jordan River flows from the north into the northern part of this sea. The water is so salty that no living organism inhabits it.

SaltValley.desc: A valley located south of the Dead Sea where several battles with the Edomites took place.

Samaria.desc: Samaria City: A city constructed by King Omri which was the capital of the northern Israelite kingdom until it was conquered by Assyrians; often used to refer to the entire northern kingdom.

Samaria.2.desc: A region in the central part of Palestine, between Galilee and the Dead Sea, named after its capital city;

Samos.desc: An island off the west coast of Asia Minor; Paul's ship stopped here during his third missionary journey.

Samothrace.desc: An island in the northern Aegean Sea; Paul's ship stopped here on his journey from Troas to Philippi.

Sansannah.desc: A town in the southern territory of Judah, near the border of Edom.

Sardis.desc: A city in western Asia Minor; one of the seven cities addressed in Revelation.

Sarid.desc: A location in the territory of Zebulun.

Scillium.desc: A town in northern Africa; home of the Scillitan Martyrs.

Sebaste.desc: A city in Asia Minor where forty soldiers were martyred in the fourth century; modern-day Sivas, Turkey.

Secacah.desc: A town in the wilderness of the territory of Judah.

Secu.desc: The location of a large cistern in the territory of Benjamin.

Seir.desc: Seir Region: A mountainous area east of the Jordan Valley and south of Moab, first inhabited by the Horites and later by the Edomites.

SeirMount.desc: Mount Seir of Edom: A mountain range in Edom.

SeirMount.2.desc: Mount Seir of Judah: A mountain in the territory of Judah.

Seirah.desc: A town or area in the hill country of Ephraim where Ehud escaped to after he killed Eglon, king of Moab.

Sela.desc: Sela of the Amorites: A location on the border of the territory of the Amorites.

Seleucia.desc: The port city of Antioch in Syria; Paul and Barnabas departed for Cyprus from here.

Senaah.desc: A location where some of those who returned from exile with Zerubbabel originally came from; exact meaning unsure.

Seneh.desc: A steep rock face near Michmash, facing another rock named Bozez.

Senir.desc: A mountain of the Anti-Lebanon range, located north-east of Israel; also known as Hermon, Sion, and Sirion.

Sennabris.desc: A settlement on the southern shore of the Sea of Galilee.

Sephar.desc: A location, likely in South Arabia, that served as one of the boundaries of the territory belonging to the descendants of Joktan.

Sepharad.desc: A town, identified with Sardis in Lydia by some, located in Media or Spain by others; place where some of the inhabitants of Jerusalem were exiled (ABD).

Sepharvaim.desc: A town from which inhabitants were relocated to Samaria by the king of Assyria.

Sepphoris.desc: A village on the southwestern shore of the Sea of Galilee.

Seville.desc: A Roman city in southwestern Spain.

Shaalbim.desc: A town in the territory of Dan during the time of King Solomon, under control of Ben-Deker.

Shaalbon.desc: Home of Eliahba, one of David's fighting men; possible the same as Shaalbim.

Shaalim.desc: A region in the territory of Benjamin where Saul looked for his father's donkeys (1 Samuel 9:4)

Shaaraim.desc: Shaaraim of Judah: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Shaaraim.2.desc: Shaaraim of Simeon: A town in the territory of Simeon.

Shahazumah.desc: A town in the territory of Issachar.

Shalishah.desc: A region in the territory of Ephraim where Saul looked for his father's donkeys (1 Samuel 9:4).

Shallecheth.desc: A gate on the western side of the temple in Jerusalem; also known as the West Gate.

Shamir.desc: Shamir of Judah: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah.

Shamir.2.desc: Shamir of Ephraim: A town in the hill country of the territory of Ephraim; residence of Tola, son of Puah, judge of Israel.

Shaphir.desc: A town in the territory of Ephraim.

Sharon.desc: Sharon of Gad: An area of pasturelands in the territory of Gad.

Sharon.2.desc: A plain along the coast of the Mediterranean.

Sharuhen.desc: A town in the territory of Simeon.

Shaveh.desc: A valley near Salem where Abraham met Melchizedek (Genesis 14:17); also known as the King's Valley.

Sheba.desc: A town in the territory of Simeon.

Sheba.2.desc: Sheba of Arabia: A country known for its wealth and actively involved in trading; regarded as descendants of a man with the same name; its queen visited King Solomon; exact location unknown.

Shebarim.desc: A location near Ai where the men of Ai chased the Israelites.

Shechem.desc: A Levitical town of refuge in the hill country of the territory of Ephraim; assigned to the clan of Kohath. God appeared to Abram at Shechem and Abram built an altar.

SheepGate.desc: A gate in the walls of Jerusalem, near the pool of Bethesda, which was rebuilt by the high priest Eliashib and his fellow priests (Nehemiah 3:1).

Shema.desc: A town in the southern territory of Judah, near the border of Edom.

Shen.desc: A location near where Samuel set up the Ebenezer stone, near Mizpah.

Shepham.desc: A location along the eastern boundary of Israel.

Shephelah.desc: The area between the hill country and the coastal plain, which consists of foothills; literally "the lowland," named thus by the Israelites who occupied the hill country; known for its olive trees and sycamore trees.

ShepherMount.desc: A mountain on the Sinai Peninsula where the Israelites camped during their journey through the wilderness (Numbers 33:23–24).

Shihor.desc: A river in the northeastern delta region of Egypt.

Shihor-libnath.desc: A small river running northeast of the Carmel range and forming the western boundary of the territory of Asher.

Shikkeron.desc: A town on the northern border of the territory of Judah.

Shilhim.desc: A town in the southern territory of Judah.

Shiloah.desc: A pool in Jerusalem receiving water from the Gihon Spring.

Shiloh.desc: A town in the territory of Ephraim; location of the Tent of Meeting for some time.

Shimron.desc: A town in Canaan that fought with the Israelites at the Waters of Merom; possibly to be identified with Shimron-Meron.

Shimron-meron.desc: A town in Canaan conquered by Joshua and the Israelites; possibly to be identified with Shimron.

Shinar.desc: A region in Mesopotamia between the Euphrates and Tigris rivers; another name for Babylonia.

Shion.desc: A town in the territory of Issachar.

Shittim.desc: A location on the plains of Moab, across from Jericho, where the Israelites camped before crossing the Jordan River (JOS 3:1).

Shual.desc: A region or district in the territory of Benjamin.

Shunem.desc: A town in the territory of Issachar.

Sibmah.desc: A village in the territory of Reuben; also known as Sebam.

Sibraim.desc: A town between Damascus and Hamath, Syria.

SiddimValley.desc: A valley, part of the Jordan Valley, where the kings of Sodom and Gomorrah and their allies came together to fight the kings from the east (Genesis 14:1–10); after Sodom and Gomorrah were destroyed this valley turned into the Salt Sea.

Sidon.desc: A seaport town on the Phoenician coast, north of Tyre; marked the northern boundary of the promised land.

Siloam.desc: The name for a system of water supply in Jerusalem; the pool of Siloam was probably the basin into which the water flowed.

Sin.desc: A desert in the Sinai Peninsula, between the Sea of Reeds and Dophkah, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan.

SinaiMount.desc: A mountain and surrounding desert on the Sinai Peninsula in Egypt where YHWH entered into a covenant with Israel; also known as Mount Horeb.

SinaiWilderness.desc: A desert region in the Sinai Peninsula, near Mount Sinai, through which the Israelites traveled during the exodus.

Siphmoth.desc: A town in the territory of Judah where David sent plunder.

Sirah.desc: A pit or cistern located not far from Hebron from where Abner was asked to return to Hebron by messengers from Joab.

Sitnah.desc: A well dug by herdsmen of Isaac, which became a source of contention between them and the herdsmen of Gerar.

Smyrna.desc: A city on the west coast of Asia Minor; one of the seven cities addressed in Revelation.

Socoh.desc: Socoh in the Shephelah: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Socoh.2.desc: Socoh of Judah: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah.

Socoh.3.desc: Socoh in the Sharon Plain: A town in one of Solomon's districts, in the Sharon Plain.

Sodom.desc: A town near the Dead Sea where Lot settled when he separated himself from Abraham; it was destroyed with Gomorrah.

SolomonsPortico.desc: A colonnade on the east side of the Herod's temple in Jerusalem.

SorekValley.desc: A valley west of Jerusalem; home of Delila, Samson's lover (Judges 16:4).

South.desc: South towards the Negev: A cardinal direction indicating the direction to the right of a person facing the direction of the rising sun, which is the direction of the Negev desert.

South.2.desc: South Kingdom of Sheba: Another name for Sheba.

South.3.desc: South Kingdom of Ptolemy: A kingdom mentioned in the book of Daniel; probably a reference to Egypt.

Spain.desc: A country at the western end of the Mediterranean Sea; Paul planned to travel there after visiting Jerusalem.

StAlbans.desc: A city in England, northwest of modern-day London, named after the first British martyr.

StoneOfZoheleth.desc: A stone or rock located near En-Rogel, south of Jerusalem; where David's son Adonijah tried to make himself king.

Straight.desc: A street in Damascus where the apostle Paul stayed after encountering the risen Christ.

Subiaco.desc: A town in central Italy where the Abbey of Saint Scholastica, also known as Subiaco Abbey, is located. The abbey was founded by Saint Benedict of Nursia.

Succoth.desc: Succoth of Gad: A town in the territory of Gad.

Succoth.2.desc: Succoth of Egypt: A location in eastern Egypt, between Ramees and Etham; first campsite of the Israelites on their way from Egypt to Canaan.

Suph.desc: A location in the wilderness facing the location where Moses was said to deliver his speech found in Deuteronomy.

Suphah.desc: A location in Moab mentioned in Numbers 21:14.

Sur.desc: A gate in Jerusalem, possibly leading from the royal palace to the temple; another name for the Gate of the Foundation.

Sychar.desc: A city in Samaria where Jesus spoke to the Samaritan Woman at Jacob's Well.

Syene.desc: A town in Egypt; possibly Syrene.

Synnada.desc: A town in the region of Phrygia in Asia Minor.

Syracuse.desc: A city on the east coast of Sicily where Paul stayed for three days while on his way to Rome.

Syria.desc: A region to the north and east of Palestine; known as Aram in the Old Testament.

Syrtis.desc: Two shallow and treacherous Mediterranean gulfs along the North African coastline; Paul's ship was wrecked on Malta after attempting to avoid running aground here.

Taanach.desc: A Levitical town in the territory of Manasseh, west of the Jordan River; assigned to the clan of Kohath.

Taanath-shiloh.desc: A town in the territory of Ephraim.

Tabbath.desc: A town in the Jordan Valley, the region where Midianite soldiers fled from Gideon's army.

Tabbur-erez.desc: A mountain near Shechem; to be identified with Mount Gerizim.

Taberah.desc: A location along the route of the exodus.

Tabor.desc: Tabor of Zebulun: A Levitical town in the territory of Zebulun.

Tabor.2.desc: A tree where Saul met three men shortly after having been anointed king.

TaborMount.desc: A mountain in the territory of Naphtali, northeast of the Jezreel Valley, where Deborah and Barak launched an attack against Sisera's army (Judges 4:12–16).

Tadmor.desc: An oasis city built by Solomon in the wilderness.

Tahath.desc: A location along the route of the exodus, between Makheloth and Terah, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan.

Tahpanhes.desc: A town in Egypt on the eastern edge of the Nile Delta.

Tamar.desc: Tamar in the Wilderness: A town rebuilt by Solomon in the wilderness; possibly in the territory of Judah.

Tamar.2.desc: Tamar of Ezekiel: A town at the southwestern end of the Dead Sea; mentioned in Ezekiel as marking the southeastern boundary of Israel.

Tappuah.desc: Tappuah of Ephraim: A town in the territory of Ephraim on the border of the territory of Manasseh.

Tappuah.2.desc: Tappuah of Judah: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Taralah.desc: A town in the territory of Benjamin.

Tarentum.desc: A Greek seaport city in southern Italy.

Tarraco.desc: A seaport city on the eastern coast of Spain; modern-day Tarragona.

Tarshish.desc: A seaport town or maritime region probably located at the Iberian Peninsula; described as inhabited by descendants of Javan, son of Japheth; famous for its commerce.

Tarsus.desc: The capital city of Cilicia in southeast Asia Minor; birthplace of the apostle Paul.

Tekoa.desc: A town in the territory of Judah; hometown of the prophet Amos.

Tel-abib.desc: A location near the Chebar River in Babylonia.

Tel-harsha.desc: A town in Babylon from which a group of Jews returned to Israel.

Tel-melah.desc: A town in Babylon from which a group of Jews returned to Israel.

Telassar.desc: A land conquered by the king of Assyria.

Telem.desc: A town in the territory of Judah, probably about 50 km south of Hebron, in the Negev; probably identical to Telaim.

Tema.desc: A region in northern Arabia, identified with Tayma, an oasis; founded by one of Abraham's sons.

Teman.desc: The territory of the most prominent tribe of Edom (ABD); sometimes used to refer to the entire territory of Edom.

Terah.desc: A location in the Sinai Peninsula, between Tahath and Mithkah; where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan.

TerritoryOfAsher.desc: The land assigned to the tribe of Asher.

TerritoryOfBenjamin.desc: The land assigned to the tribe of Benjamin.

TerritoryOfDan.desc: The land assigned to the tribe of Dan.

TerritoryOfEastManasseh.desc: The land assigned to the tribe of Manasseh, east of the Jordan River.

TerritoryOfEphraim.desc: The land assigned to the tribe of Ephraim.

TerritoryOfGad.desc: The land assigned to the tribe of Gad.

TerritoryOfIssachar.desc: The land assigned to the tribe of Issachar.

TerritoryOfJudah.desc: The land assigned to the tribe of Judah.

TerritoryOfNaphtali.desc: The land assigned to the tribe of Naphtali.

TerritoryOfReuben.desc: The land assigned to the tribe of Reuben.

TerritoryOfSimeon.desc: The land assigned to the tribe of Judah.

TerritoryOfWestManasseh.desc: The land assigned to the tribe of Manasseh, west of the Jordan River.

TerritoryOfZebulun.desc: The land assigned to the tribe of Zebulun.

TheLordWillProvide.desc: The place where Abraham sacrificed a ram instead of his son Isaac.

Thebes.desc: A town in Egypt; center of worship of the Egyptian deity Amon.

Thebez.desc: A town near Shechem; captured by Abimelech, son of Gideon.

Thessalonica.desc: A seaport city in Macedonia between Berea and Apollonia; 1 and 2 Thessalonians were addressed to the church there.

Theveste.desc: A Roman city in northern Africa; modern-day Tébessa, Algeria.

ThreeTaverns.desc: A location on the Appian Way where Paul was welcomed by Christians from Rome.

Thyatira.desc: A city in Lydia in Asia Minor; home of Lydia, a convert of Paul, and one of the seven cities addressed in Revelation.

Tiberias.desc: A city on the west shore of the Sea of Galilee, south of Magdala.

Tibhath.desc: A town in the kingdom of Zobah during the time of King David.

Tigris.desc: A large body of flowing water in Mesopotamia; one of the four rivers that flowed out of the river from the Garden of Eden.

Timnah.desc: Timnah near Enaim: A town near Enaim, where Judah encountered his daughter-in-law Tamar.

Timnah.1.desc: Timnah of Dan: A town in the territory of Dan, on the northern border of the territory of Judah; occupied by the Philistines and home to wife of Samson.

Timnah.2.desc: Timnah of Judah: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah.

Timnath-heres.desc: A town in the territory of Ephraim; also known as Timnath-Serah.

Tingi.desc: A seaport city on the northwestern coast of Africa; modern-day Tangier, Morocco.

Tiphsah.desc: Tiphsah of Solomon: A town at the northeastern boundary of Solomon's kingdom.

Tiphsah.2.desc: Tiphsah of Menahem: A town conquered by Menahem, king of Israel.

Tirzah.desc: A city in the territory of Manasseh; capital of the northern kingdom of Israel during the reign of King Jeroboam until the reign of King Omri, who moved the capital to Samaria.

Tishbe.desc: A place in Gilead; home of the prophet Elijah.

Tob.desc: A town or territory east of the northern Jordan River.

Tochen.desc: A village in the territory of Simeon.

Toletum.desc: A city on the Tagus River in Spain; modern-day Toledo.

Tophel.desc: A location in the Arabah not far from the place where Moses repeated the law.

Topheth.desc: A location in the valley of Hinnom associated with child sacrifices to Molech.

TowerOfEder.desc: A location near Jerusalem and Bethlehem, possibly a somewhat elevated place from which one could overlook a relatively large area of land.

TowerOfShechem.desc: A fortress in the town of Shechem.

TowerOfTheHundred.desc: A tower in part of the wall of Jerusalem protecting the northern approach to the city (ABD).

TowerOfTheOvens.desc: A tower located in the bakers' quarter in northwestern Jerusalem.

Trapezus.desc: A city on the southern coast of the Black Sea in Asia Minor; modern-day Trabzon, Turkey.

TravelersValley.desc: A valley where the armies of Gog will be buried, according to a prophecy of Ezekiel (Ezekiel 39:11).

Troas.desc: A city and region in the northwest corner of Asia Minor; Paul had a vision while visiting there (Acts 16:8–9).

Trogyllium.desc: A promontory and settlement near the island of Samos.

Tubal.desc: A nation possibly to be identified with Tabal, located in vicinity of the Black Sea; considered descendants of Japheth through his son Tubal.

Tyre.desc: A seaport town on the Phoenician coast, south of Sidon.

Ulai.desc: An irrigation canal located in the province Elam of the Persian Empire, near Susa.

Ummah.desc: A town in the territory of Asher.

Uphaz.desc: A region known for its gold.

UpperGulloth.desc: A spring given to Achsah by her father Caleb as a wedding gift.

Uqnu.desc: A river in southern Mesopotamia; possibly the Karkheh.

Ur.desc: Ur Town: A town on the Euphrates River in southern Mesopotamia, where Abraham and his family used to live before moving to Haran.

Uzal.desc: A nation or area either to be considered founded by a person with the same name and located somewhere on the Arabian Peninsula, or to be identified with Izalla in northeastern Mesopotamia; trading partner of Tyre (ABD).

Uzza.desc: A garden, which was part of palace compound of King Manasseh, where Manasseh and his son Amon were buried.

Uzzen-sheerah.desc: A town built by Sheerah, daughter of Ephraim.

Valencia.desc: A seaport city on the eastern coast of Spain.

ValleyGate.desc: A gate through which Nehemiah passed to inspect the walls of Jerusalem (Nehemiah 2:13).

ValleyOfDecision.desc: A valley east of Jerusalem; also known as the Valley of Jehoshaphat.

ValleyOfGerar.desc: A valley near the town of Gerar, in the Negev, where Isaac settled for a time (Genesis 26:17).

ValleyOfJehoshaphat.desc: A valley east of Jerusalem; also as the Valley of Decision.

labels: Valley of the Son of Hinnom
valley of the children of Hinnom
ValleyOfSlaughter.desc: A valley, also known as the Hinnom Valley, known for the idol worship that took place there.

Vercellae.desc: A city in northwestern Italy; modern-day Vercelli.

Vindobona.desc: A Roman military camp in the region of Pannonia; modern-day Vienna.

Vivarium.desc: A monastery founded by Cassiodorus in southern Italy.

Waheb.desc: An unidentified location, probably in Moab near the Arnon River (ABD).

WashersField.desc: A location outside of Jerusalem during King Hezekiah's day, near a road and an aqueduct to the upper pool; cloth materials were cleaned and processed there.

WaterGate.desc: An eastern gate in Jerusalem where Ezra read the Law before the returned exiles (Nehemiah 8:1–3).

WatersOfJericho.desc: A spring or river near Jericho.

WayOfHoliness.desc: A road envisioned in Isa 35:8 that leads to Zion.

WayOfTheRedSea.desc: A road between the Dead Sea and the Gulf of Aqaba.

WestGate.desc: A gate on the western side of the temple in Jerusalem; also known as Shallecheth Gate.

WildernessOfMaon.desc: A wilderness in the territory of Judah near the town of Maon.

WildernessOfParan.desc: A desert located south of Israel, west of Edom, and north of the wilderness of Sinai.

WildgoatsRocks.desc: A location in the desert of Judah where Saul looked for David.

YeshanahGate.desc: A gate in Jerusalem which was repaired by Johoida and Meshullam (Nehemiah 3:6).

Yiron.desc: A fortified town in the territory of Naphtali.

Zaanan.desc: A town in the territory of Judah; also known as Zenan.

Zaanannim.desc: A town in the territory of Naphtali.

Zair.desc: A town in the territory of Judah, near the border with Edom.

Zalmon.desc: A mountain mentioned in Psalm 68:14; possibly another name for Mount Zalmon near Shechem (Judges 9:48), or Mount Hermon.

ZalmonMount.desc: A mountain near Shechem where Abimelech and his men cut wood to burn the tower of Shechem (Judges 9:48).

Zalmonah.desc: A location along the route of the exodus, between Mount Hor and Punon, where the Israelites encamped on their way from Egypt to Canaan.

Zanoah.desc: Zanoah in the Shephelah: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah.

Zanoah.2.desc: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah, founded by Jekuthiel.

Zaphon.desc: Zaphon of Gad: A town in the territory of Gad.

Zaphon.2.desc: A mountain associated with the Canaanite god Baal, located at the Syria-Turkey border near the mouth of the Orontes River.

Zarephath.desc: A town located between Tyre and Sidon; Phoenician seaport. God sent Elijah to meet a widow there (1 Kings 17:9).

Zarethan.desc: A town in the Jordan Valley, in the territory of Ephraim; also known as Zeredah and Zererah.

Zeboiim.desc: A town near the Dead Sea; destroyed with Sodom and Gomorrah.

Zeboim.desc: A town or village in the territory of Benjamin.

ZeboimValley.desc: A valley in the territory of Benjamin.

Zedad.desc: A town located on the northern boundary of Israel, perhaps 105 km northeast of Damascus; part of Israel only during the reigns of David and Solomon; regarded as part of the restored nation in Ezekiel's vision.

Zela.desc: A town in the territory of Benjamin.

Zelzah.desc: A location in the territory of Benjamin near Rachel's tomb.

Zemaraim.desc: A town in the territory of Benjamin.

Zenan.desc: A town in the foothills of the territory of Judah; also known as Zaanan.

Zephath.desc: A town in Canaan captured and destroyed by Judah and Simeon; renamed Hormah.

ZephathahValley.desc: A valley near Mareshah in the Shephelah where Asa fought with Zerah the Cushite (2 Chronicles 14:9).

Zer.desc: A fortified town in the territory of Naphtali.

Zered.desc: A valley of the wadi of the same name, located south of Moab; crossed by the Israelites, ending their 40 years of sojourn in the wilderness.

Zeredah.desc: Zeredah in the Jordan Valley: A town in the Jordan Valley, in the territory of Ephraim.

Zeredah.2.desc: Zeredah of Jeroboam: A town in the territory of Ephraim; home of Jeroboam.

Zererah.desc: A town in the Jordan Valley, in the territory of Ephraim, toward which the Midianites fled from Gideon and his army.

Zereth-shahar.desc: A town in the territory of Reuben.

Ziddim.desc: A fortified town in the territory of Naphtali.

Ziklag.desc: A town in the territory of Simeon which belonged to Philistia and was given to David before he moved to Hebron, where he was made king of Judah; precise location is unknown.

Zimri.desc: A nation, possibly to be linked with Zimran, son of Abraham and Keturah; or possibly a substitution cipher, where the letters of the alphabet are reversed (atbash), for Elam.

Zin.desc: A wilderness area in the Negev on the southern border of Canaan, near Kadesh-Barnea.

Zion.desc: A name referring to parts or all of Jerusalem; sometimes used to refer to Israel as a whole.

labels: mountain of the house of the Lord
heights where the Temple now stands
ZionMount.desc: A hill in Jerusalem where the temple was built; also the location of the fortification known as the City of David (2 Samuel 6:7).

Zior.desc: A town in the hill country of the territory of Judah.

Ziph.desc: Ziph of Judah: A town in the southern territory of Judah, near the border of Edom.

Ziph.2.desc: A wilderness region surrounding a town of the same name, near Hebron in the territory of Judah.

Ziphron.desc: A location along the northern boundary of Israel.

Ziz.desc: A steep mountain pass in southern Judah near En-Gedi, the shortest route from Moab to Judah, near Tekoa; used by the Moabites, Ammonites, and Meunites to attack king Jehoshaphat and his forces (2 Chronicles20:16).

Zoan.desc: A town in the Nile Delta of Egypt; Egyptian capital during the 21st and 22nd dynasties, and the administrative center of Lower Egypt.

Zoar.desc: A town in the southern Jericho Valley, on the south bank of the Wadi Zered in Edomite territory.

Zobah.desc: An Aramean kingdom located north of Damascus and ruled by Hadadezer; it was defeated and subjugated by David and then controlled by Solomon.

Zophim.desc: A field at the top of Mount Pisgah in Moab; one of the places from where Balaam was to curse Israel.

Zorah.desc: A town in the foothills of the territory of Dan.

Zuph.desc: Zuph Region: A region probably located in the territory of Ephraim, where Saul searched for his father's donkeys (1 Samuel 9:5).
